<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Gold Demand Rises 17.1 Pct in Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- World gold demand rose by 17.1
percent to a record 2,028 tons in the first half of this year,
according to the Gold Fields Mineral Services (GFMS) consultancy
today.
</P>
<P>
In its latest gold market update, the GFMS said that there was
also an increase in mine output in spite of low gold prices
although it was only 1.4 percent compared with the same months of
1996 at 1,161 tons.
</P>
<P>
It suggested that producer hedging, private sales and disposals
by central banks from their reserves helped to fill the growing
gap between newly mined gold and demand in the half year.
</P>
<P>
The consultancy estimated that forward sales and option hedging
by producers added 192 tons to gold supply in the first half of
this year whereas not one ton was made available in this way
during the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
There were an estimated 220 tons of net central bank sales,
including 200 tons of central bank gold whose sale has still to be
announced.
</P>
<P>
The gold market review said that the first half witnessed the
largest-ever shipment of physical gold to the Asian markets, above
all to the Middle East and India, with almost all of this being
destined for private sector purchases.
</P>
<P>
However, it added that the flow of gold from central banks,
private sellers and producer hedging is not likely to be enough to
push the gold price below present levels for any length of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
