<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage Rates Fall in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The cost of long-term
mortgages in Canada dropped today to their lowest level since
1965, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
The five-year mortgage rate drops to 6.85 percent, down 15
basis points, the lowest long-term rate available in Canada since
1965.
</P>
<P>
Loans of up to 25 years drop by as much as a quarter of a
percentage point, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The latest cuts will be a boon for first-time buyers who tend
to favor longer-term loans to have predictable carrying costs,
said a top official at Toronto-Dominion (TD) Bank.
</P>
<P>
The rate reduction came on the heels of a bond market rally
that has trimmed 15 to 20 basis points from bond yields in the
past two months.
</P>
<P>
Bond yields are a benchmark for mortgage rates because they
reflect the cost of funding the loans.
</P>
<P>
Royal Bank of Canada was the first on Monday to announce the
reduction of 15 to 25 basis points for terms of four years to 25
years.
</P>
<P>
Other commercial banks, such as TD Bank, Bank of Montreal and
Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, quickly matched the move.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
