<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian, Egyptian Presidents Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin and his Egyptian counterpart Hosni Mubarak today signed a
joint political declaration and two agreements on cooperation in
technology and crime-control, according to Interfax News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said he was confident the first official visit by the
Egyptian president to Russia since its independence "would make a
breakthrough in all areas of our cooperation".
</P>
<P>
He said his talks with Mubarak covered a wide range of issues
and the joint declaration was of considerable political
significance.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Yeltsin expressed regret that trade volume
was small for the two countries, which he put at 480 million U.S.
dollars at the moment.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East, the two presidents achieved "a high level
of mutual understanding with regard to all issues," Yeltsin's
spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Mubarak noted that he supported the implementation
of the land-for-peace formula in the Middle East and
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Peace in the Middle East will not be restored without this, he
said.
</P>
<P>
While calling on the United States to continue its effort in
the region, Yeltsin vowed that Russia will intensify its role as a
co-sponsor of the Middle East settlement in the future.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to begin work on a new treaty on
bilateral friendship and cooperation, Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky also disclosed that Russian First Deputy Prime
Minister Boris Nemtsov will visit Egypt early 1998 to discuss
trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president arrived here Monday on an official visit
aimed at reviving the traditional close ties between the two
nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
