<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Calls Evolution in Serbia "Positive" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- France today described as
"positive" the evolution in Serbia in the wake of the presidential
and legislative elections in the country held on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We have noted with satisfaction the good progress, under the
observation of the Organization of Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE), of the presidential and legislative elections in
Serbia," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
Zoran Lilic, a presidential candidate of the Socialist Party of
President Slobodan Milosevic is likely to head for a runoff
against the leader of the Radical Party Vojislav Seselj, in a
second round race on October 5, according to partial results from
the elections.
</P>
<P>
The Radical Party is also close behind the Socialists in the
race for Serbia's 250-seat Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that "on the whole, since the recognition of
the victory of the democratic opposition during the municipal
elections last winter, the evolution is positive." 
</P>
</TEXT>
