<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana's President Calls on Africans to Live </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian President Jerry
Rawlings has called on Africans to live modestly although there
may be no legal sanctions against the display of affluence and
materialism.
</P>
<P>
"We all have a fundamental duty to live modestly, given our
continent's turbulent historical fight against corruption,"
Rawlings said in Accra, capital of Ghana, on Monday at the
opening of the 5th African conference of ombudsmen.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference, themed "the importance of
administrative justice in the democratization process in Africa",
is being attended by delegates from 17 African countries,
according to a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings told the participants that the ordinary citizen's
conformity to law and order "depends on the transparency of the
public official's integrity".
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the arbitration role of traditional councils
must be given the chance to reduce the volume of court cases,
saying: "I sincerely believe that there is need and room for our
traditional process of arbitration to contribute to our
democractic process and delivery of social justice."
</P>
<P>
According to Rawlings, Africa's modernization has seen the
erosion of traditional values and practices which in the past
provided protection for both the individual and community.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, taboos and moral edicts were sufficient
deterrents for various crimes. Today, neither our elaborate
criminal codes nor court punishments against social malpratices
have deterred their occurrence. Rather, they are on the
increase," Rawlings said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that democracy and administrative justice are,
therefore, guaranteed not only by formal institutions, some of
which tend to be alien to African culture, but also require the
responsibility or good will of the individual.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
