<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Won's New Low Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean won today
plunged to a new low against the U.S. dollar after three days of
consecutive decrease, threatening to break the 915-won level.
</P>
<P>
The won fell in today's trading to as low as 914.50 won against
one dollar, the lowest since the nation introduced an average
market rate system in March 1990.
</P>
<P>
The nation's top bank official argued that such changes in
foreign exchange rate have not reached a worrisome level and the
situation would be stable soon.
</P>
<P>
The main reason to the depreciation was the massive buying of
dollars by local traders.
</P>
<P>
The won-dollar parity rate has been down by 7.6 percent since
the end of last year, when the figure was 844.20 won against one
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Despite the central bank's strong intervention, market
participants predict that the won's declination would last until
the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
However, Lee Kyong-shik, Governor of the Bank of Korea,
indicated that the situation is all right, saying that though the
won has inched down continuously lately, the declining pace is
almost the same as that of Japanese yen against the dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
