<HEADLINE> Qian Meets With South African Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen met with South African Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo here today, with both sides appreciating the
smooth development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
It was very appreciable that President Nelson Mandela and the
South African government decided to establish diplomatic relations
with China under the principle of "One China," said Qian, who is
attending the 52nd session of the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Establishment of diplomatic relations was in accordance with
the fundamental interests of the people of the two nations and
will provide necessary conditions for the two sides to conduct
cooperation in various fields, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Qian also appreciated Nzo's efforts in pushing forward the
normalization of relations between China and South Africa and his
positive attitude on the "One China" principle.
</P>
<P>
Qian noted that South Africa has an important role in the
regional and international affairs. After the establishment of
diplomatic relations, the two countries could conduct cooperation
in many areas, and enhance consultations and cooperation
in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Nzo said that the decision of the South African government to
establish diplomatic ties with China can never be changed. After
the normalization of the bilateral relations, he said, the
potentials of cooperation can be brought into full play, bringing
lots of benefit to the people of both countries.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are being engaged in economic and trade
exchanges, which can be promoted to a bigger scale after the
establishment of the diplomatic links, according to Nzo, who added
that the two countries can have effective cooperation in the
affairs of the United Nations and on other international arenas.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is a reliable friend of Africa. For a long
time, China has been in sympathy with and support the African
people. South Africa hopes to continue to develop its cooperation
with China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
