<HEADLINE> France Urges Cameroun's Opposition to Join Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- France today called on
Cameroun's opposition parties to join the presidential election to
be held on October 12 and urged the authorities to organize a
"free, open and transparent" election.
</P>
<P>
"The decision by Cameroun's opposition parties not to
participate in the next presidential election does not seem to
help a harmonious functioning of a democratic system," said French
Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
But he said that France does not want to meddle with the
"organization and functioning of the electoral consultations" in
Cameroun.
</P>
<P>
French officials have told leader of the Camerounian opposition
Social Democratic Front John Fru Ndi that, "the existence of
dialogue between the power and the opposition is needed for the
functioning of a democratic system," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ndi, who earlier indicated that he would boycott the election
because of the refusal by President Paul Biya to set up an
independent electoral commission, made a visit to France on Monday
to seek advice from French government on the election.
</P>
<P>
It is for the Camerounian government to decide whether the
regularity of voting will be better ensured by the presence of a
national independent electoral commission, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that France considers it necessary for Cameroun to
find a "lasting consensus to implement the democratic system."
</P>
</TEXT>
