<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin-Gore Commission Session Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The ninth session of the
Russian-U.S. joint commission on economic and technical
cooperation (Chernomyrdin-Gore commission) wound up here today
with more than 15 inter-governmental and inter-departmental
agreements signed.
</P>
<P>
According to the Itar-Tass news agency, both Russian Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and U.S. Vice President Albert Gore
were satisfied with the results of the session.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Chernomyrdin said that the sides had
managed to considerably move ahead in major directions.
</P>
<P>
This includes mutual access to each other's markets, the
development of investment cooperation, assistance in Russia's
integration into the world economy as well as international
economic and financial bodies, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin and Gore today signed a joint declaration about
the future work of their commission till the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the press conference, Gore said that an agreement
which will halt the production of weapons-grade plutonium by the
end of the decade was signed by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
This means, Gore said, three Russian reactors producing
weapons-grade plutonium in Russia will be converted to civilian
use by the end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also forecasted an investment boom in Russia in
the next few months or years. Gore said a great role in this shall
be played by the new Russian tax legislation, protection of
investors' rights and successful measures against crime and
corruption.
</P>
<P>
American investments in the Russian economy increased several
times in the first half of this year. Now they make one third of
the overall foreign investments in the Russian economy, according
to Gore.
</P>
<P>
Al Gore arrived in Moscow last Sunday for three days to
co-chair along with Chernomyrdin the session of the Russian-U.S.
commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
