<HEADLINE> Military Situation in Angola "Quiet" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Joint Committee for
Angolan Peace process said today that the military situation in
Angola is basically quiet,
</P>
<P>
The committee made the conclusion at a meeting on national
situation.
</P>
<P>
The meeting mainly discussed issues concerning the
re-establishment of national authoritative institutions in areas
occupied by the former rebel movement UNITA and the registration
and disarmament of UNITA's remaining militiamen.
</P>
<P>
The committee expressed satisfaction over the re-establishment
of national authority in 79 regions occupied by UNITA. Both the
government and UNITA agreed that regional governments will be
established in Uige and Lunda-Norte provinces on September 29 and
30.
</P>
<P>
It is disclosed at the meeting that up to now, 3,341 UNITA
fighters have participated in registration. They have also handed
over 3,031 pieces of various weapons.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the committee was worried about the competence of
the militiamen and quality of their weapons.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that the Angolan government and the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) are accusing
each other of small-scale military operations in some provinces,
situation in the whole country is basically "quiet".
</P>
<P>
The meeting also expressed satisfaction about the decision by
the Angolan government to collect weapons from citizens living in
UNITA-occupied areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
