<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Council of European Union Backs Annan's Reform Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Council of
European Union welcomed U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
wide-range proposals for the reform of the United Nations, the
council's President Jacqure F. Poos said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 52nd session of the General Assembly, the
president said the secretary-general's ambitious proposals were
aimed to transform the organization into high-achieving, efficient
instrument at the service of all the people of the world.
</P>
<P>
"We need an organization that can carry out its mandate to
preserve peace and security in a faster and more effective way,
while building better capacities for actions in the fields of
preventive diplomacy, peace-keeping and peace-making and, has
more effective capacities of contributing to rehabilitation and
reconstruction after a conflict," said the president.
</P>
<P>
"We need an organization that is able to respond more
adequately to one of its fundamental objectives, which is
promoting economic and social progress, eradicating poverty and
ensure the widest possible participation in an expanding world
economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "We need a UN system that offers a credible
response to the complex problems of human assistance and
emergency situations, which include conflict prevention,
peace-keeping, rehabilitation and transition towards development."
</P>
<P>
The president said that to obtain the objectives, the
organization would have to be able to rely not only on the
commitment of the secretary-general and the cooperation of the
member states, but on the support of all sectors of the
international society, and in particular on the non-governmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Council of European Union did not intend to
press for the fine points of its own positions to be taken into
account in each of the proposals or recommendations which were on
the table. But it hoped the other countries would approach this
exercise in a similar spirit, and they could agree to put the
general positive trust of the package of proposals before the
satisfaction of their individual demands.
</P>
<P>
On the financial crisis of the organization, the president said
it could not be solved until all the member states had agreed to
meet their obligations under the United Nations Charter in fully,
by discharging the arrears which they owe and by paying on time
and without conditions the full amount of their mandatory
contributions to the organization's regular budget and to the
budget of peacekeeping operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
