<HEADLINE> Somali Faction Leader Returns to Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The delegation led by
Abdurahman Ahmed Ali Tuur, deputy president of Somali faction
leader Hussein Aidid, reached the capital Mogadishu, late this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which according to the authority of the break
away republic of Somaliland, have been deported today, consisted
of six cabinet ministers of Hussein Aidid's unrecognized
government.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after his arrival, Tuur, who looked very tired, made a
brief statement at his residence in south Mogadishu, saying his
tour in the northwestern regions of Somalia was completed as
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Tuur, who smoked one cigarette after another, told Xinhua that
his delegation have attended a luncheon with more than 60
ministers (of the break away republic), intellectuals and
traditional elders from Hargeisa and discussed with them about
the federal system for the first time.
</P>
<P>
They also talked about the security in the northwestern
regions.
</P>
<P>
Tuur said the delegation had planned to return to Mogadishu
today, and Egal (president of the break away republic of
Somaliland) himself knew about the departure plan.
</P>
<P>
"We were shocked by the news broadcast by Radio Hargeisa
telling my delegation to leave within 24 hours," said Tuur, who
admitted that he and his delegation were warmly received in
Hargeisa, adding that "We were seen off warmly".
</P>
<P>
This move by Egal, according to Tuur, is not any different
from an earlier death sentence he made against me and Jama
Mohamed Qalib, foreign minister of Hussein Aidid's self-crowned
government.
</P>
<P>
"The death sentence became impossible and so this will be," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about whether he will again go back to Somaliland, Tuur
said, "Of course this will not be my last visit and more visits
will follow."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Tuur said the statement made by Egal last night will
only mess the security situation in those regions.
</P>
<P>
"We are working towards the pacification of our regions and
Somalia in general," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
