<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Publishes Sustainable Development Indicators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Most European Union
countries have to rely heavily on non-renewable resources of
energy, which is predicted to be unsustainable in the long term.
</P>
<P>
The prediction was made today by Eurostat, the statistic arm of
the 15-nation union. The agency said that EU consumption of
renewable energy accounts for a mere 5 percent of total energy
consumption.
</P>
<P>
The consumption of renewable energy is comparatively high in
Finland, Austria and Sweden, all new members to the union, whereas
it is low in such older member states as Britain and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Sweden leads the consumption chart of renewable resources of
energy with 24 percent while Britain is at the bottom of the chart
with 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Over the last decade, the use of natural gas is up 50 percent
and 55 percent more electricity is consumed due to the boom in
electrical appliances.
</P>
<P>
European Union-wide, each person consumes an average 2,388
kilograms of oil equivalent a year as the survey showed.
</P>
<P>
The result of the EU's pilot sustainable development indicator
study, as recommended by the United Nations Commission on
Sustainable Development, showed that estimated life of EU coal
reserves is 209 years, as compared with the worldwide figure of
147 years.
</P>
<P>
Ireland's coal will last 14,000 years whereas France's will
last for only 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The estimated life of coal reserves in the United States is 126
years and it is 117 years for Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
