<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov Calls for Solutions to UN Financial Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeni Primakov today called for a quick solution to
the serious financial problems faced by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"Reform of the U.N. with an eye on its increase efficiency
would, of course, be inconceivable without overcoming financial
problems faced by the organization," Primakov said in an address
to the 52nd session of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The annual 52nd session opened last Tuesday with its general
debates focused on the reform of the largest international
organization.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister said that the U.N. financial
problems unfortunately "have become chronic." The debts owed by
some member states total 2.3 billion U.S. dollars, according to a
press release by the United Nations Informations Department.
</P>
<P>
The United States reportedly owes some 1.5 billion U.S. dollars
to the world body.
</P>
<P>
"It should be emphasized that all member states are responsible
for the UN financial health and that all of them must pay their
dues properly," Primakov stressed.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the widely-discussed reforms of the United
Nations, Primakov said that Russians "are in favor of expanding
the Security Council membership."
</P>
<P>
But he cautioned that such an expansion should not "render our
organization less efficient."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council now consists of 15 members, five of
which are permanent ones. Several proposals have been put
forward for the reforms of the council.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said that he hopes the U.N. reform will take place
against the background of an ever increasing role of regional
organization. Such a reform would be "logical process," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We see the U.N. in the 21st century as a highly efficient
organization free from bureaucratic constraints, as a pro-active
organization capable of swiftly responding to the challenges of
the contemporary world," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
