<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov: Russia Favors New Multipolar World Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeni Primakov today stressed that his nation favors
and has been making efforts for a new multipolar world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the general debates of the 52nd session of the U.N.
General Assembly, Primakov said, "It is essential to create
conditions that would bring stability to a new world order."
</P>
<P>
He said that in the present-day world, no country in the world
should hold a monopoly on any conflict resolution effort.
</P>
<P>
"This fully applies to the longest standing conflict in the
Middle East where the settlement process has been stalemated," the
Russian foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that "broad-based international efforts
are needed" to undo the tight Middle East knot.
</P>
<P>
"As one of the co-sponsors of the peace process launched in
1991 in Madrid, Russia is prepared to cooperate actively with
everyone to attain this goal," said Primakov.
</P>
<P>
He said that a synergy of efforts will provide the shortest cut
to the resolution of both long-standing and relatively new
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Primakov indicated that Russia will work together with the
United States to complete demolishing the hurdles of the past and,
above all, the legacy of the decades-long massive arms race.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the two strategic arms reduction treaties
reached with the United States, Russia is ready to move ahead
towards greater reduction, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Next on our agenda is the involvement of all nuclear powers in
systematic efforts to reduce their nuclear arms," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Primakov said that the stability of a multipolar world can be
assured not just by ending the nuclear arms race of the past.
</P>
<P>
Urgent measures are needed to prevent the proliferation of
nuclear weapons to other countries beyond nuclear powers, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
