<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspected Lassa Fever Case Arouses Fears in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- German health authorities have
put about 100 people under medical supervision after they were
found to have come into contact with a Ghanaian man suspected of
dying of a deadly disease, Lassa fever, in Germany Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old Ghanaian died Saturday in the western German
city of Mainz after admitting himself to a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
He was suspected of having been infected with the Lassa virus
which regularly hits regions of West Africa and could claim the
lives of up to 40 percent of those infected. The virus is
transmitted through rat urine or human body fluids including
sweat.
</P>
<P>
German health authorities said today that no further cases of
the disease had been found so far among the about 100 people,
including hospital staff and friends of the Ghanaian, who had
contact with him. Even the first case was still to be confirmed by
laboratory tests Wednesday or Thursday, they added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, German investigators disclosed that the Ghanaian
patient had been deported from Germany in 1993 but returned
illegally on August 7 this year. He had stayed in the city of
Duesseldorf until September 9 before taking the train to Mainz.
</P>
<P>
The incubation period of the Lassa fever ranges from three days
to three weeks. Reports said the disease could be treated
effectively if diagnosed in the first six days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
