<HEADLINE> Russian Missile Manufacturer Denies Deal With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A Russian industrial company
denied today that it will sell anti-aircraft missiles to Turkey,
the semi-official Anatolia News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Yevgeni Moskalenko, spokesman for the
Russian state-controlled Rosvoorouzhenie company, as saying that
the reports about the alleged Turkish-Russian missile deal are
"groundless."
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the Turkish government is holding
contacts with the Russian company to buy S-300 missiles.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has not said that it wants to purchase the S-300
missiles, Moskalenko said, adding, however, that his company likes
to make such a deal with Turkey if the latter wishes.
</P>
<P>
The Russian company is among more than 200 Turkish and
international firms which are here to participate in the Third
Defense Industry and Civil Aviation Fair on September 23-26.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed an agreement with the Russian company to buy
hundreds of the S-300 missiles in an unannounced date around the
beginning of the year, causing a wave of tension between the small
island country and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Both Turkey and Turkish Cypriots criticized the Cypriot
government for the missile deal, describing it as a "provocative
move."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government has said that it will use all necessary
means to block the transfer of the Russian-made missiles to the
Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot South and Turkish
Cypriot North since 1974 when Turkish troops landed and took over
the northern third of the island following a failed coup seeking
union with Greece by some Greek Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
