<HEADLINE> Nigeria Surveys Minerals for Neighboring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has completed the
compilation of the geology and mineral resources of its neighbors of
Benin, Niger, Chad and Cameroon under a regional cooperation policy.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, according to Solid Minerals Development Minister
Kaloma Ali, was carried out through his ministry, the News Agency of
Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ali also disclosed that the ministry was also cooperating with the
geological survey department of South Africa in the training of
staffers of the ministry in map production and publication of
geological map sheets for use by the Nigerian public and for the
benefit of mineral prospectors.
</P>
<P>
The minister was speaking today at the 15th Conference of Ministers
of the Association of Tin Producing Countries underway in Abjua,
capital of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He said that a team of the staff would in due course be sent to
Pretoria for training, during which they would produce geological maps
of Nigeria using South African facilities and under the guidance of
the staff of geological surveys of that country.
</P>
<P>
But "subsequently, all such maps will be produced here at home," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In consonance with global realities, he said, the Nigerian
government had put in place liberal policies and attractive mining
laws to create conducive environment for the active participation of
private investors for sustainable development of the industry.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, priorities have been given to some of
the country's mineral resources for immediate rehabilitation and
development to meet the requirements of local industries.
</P>
<P>
They include gold, bitumen, baryta, kaolin, gypsum and rock salt.
</P>
