<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US-Japan Defense Cooperation Guidelines Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Japan
today published the Guidelines for U.S.-Japan defense cooperation
in an effort to enhance their military alliance.
</P>
<P>
This was announced at a joint press conference here by U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Defense Secretary William
Cohen and their Japanese counterparts, Keizo Obuchi and Fumio
Kyuma, after a bilateral Security Consultative Committee (SCC)
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, also dubbed two plus two, discussed "a variety of
important issues of bilateral concern," including the review of
the Guidelines, according to a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 Guidelines address U.S.-Japan defense cooperation in
three areas: under normal circumstamces; "in response to an armed
attack against Japan and in response to situations in areas
surrounding Japan that have an important influence on Japan's
peace and security."
</P>
<P>
The concept "situations in areas surrounding Japan" "is not
geographic but situational, based on the nature and concept of a
particular contingency rather than its location," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The revised Guidelines made substantive changes to the 1978
version for cooperation under normal circumstances and during
situations in areas surrounding Japan.
</P>
<P>
During peacetime such items include: peacekeeping, humanitarian
relief and increases in military exchanges, officials of both
countries confirmed.
</P>
<P>
During "situations in areas surrounding Japan," their
cooperation will cover noncombatant evacuation, minesweeping,
search and rescue, rear area support and inspection of ships to
ensure enforcement of economic sanctions, the Guidelines said.
</P>
<P>
The SCC has agreed to start bilateral work immediately under
the new Guidelines by completing basic work for bilateral defense
planning, among others.
</P>
<P>
The geographic areas "surrounding Japan" that the new
Guidelines will cover remain obscure.
</P>
<P>
The enhancement of U.S.-Japan bilateral defense cooperation is
a new development in the post-war era. Other countries in Asia and
the Pacific are watching with concern how the two major military
powers will act to implement their Guidelines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
