<HEADLINE> Automobile Association Calls for Measures to Protect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The American Automobile
Association (AAA) today called for more driver education and
restricted licenses for beginners to reduce the accident toll that
claimed the lives of more than 6,000 teen-age drivers last year.
</P>
<P>
The AAA launched a Licensed to Learn campaign in an effort to
get states to tighten driving requirements for those just
learning.
</P>
<P>
People aged 15 to 20 account for just 7 percent of all drivers,
but they are involved in 14 percent of fatal crashes and 20
percent of all accidents, the association reported. The number of
teen-agers is expected to increase by 25 percent by 2012.
</P>
<P>
Most of those accidents, the AAA said, are caused by
inexperience, poor driving skills, risk-taking and poor
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
Overall, some 6,300 drivers of this age group were killed in
crashes last year in the United States -- one every 84 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The AAA said that studies show the risk of having an accident
declines sharply after someone has three to four years of driving
experience.
</P>
<P>
Some states already have their graduated licensing programs,
but most have not.
</P>
<P>
Graduated licensing programs allow youths to gain experience
and maturity while reducing risk by limiting the situations in
which they can drive.
</P>
<P>
The program urged by the AAA has three stages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
