<HEADLINE> British Foreign Secretary on UN Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook urged here today the United Nations to take
more aggressive steps to make itself more efficient,
representative and properly funded.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during the general debate of the 52nd session of the
General Assembly, Cook said that the United Nations should have a
bigger role than ever before. It must modernize. It must be able
to confront the new global challenges all its members face. "It
will need flexibility, competence and efficiency to meet the
complex needs of the 21st century," he said.
</P>
<P>
The British foreign secretary said that his country supports
the commitment of the U.N. secretary general to reform and
modernization. "Without modernizing, the U.N. will lose its
legitimacy and its effectiveness," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that making the U.N. efficient means that the
international organization does the most it can with what it has
got. The members wish to see that the U.N. no longer spends 150
million U.S. dollars producing 2,500 tons of documents every year.
"We thoroughly welcome the secretary-general's commitment to
reduce the number of documents by 25 percent by next year," he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the representativeness, the foreign secretary mainly
referred to the expansion of the Security Council, saying more
countries should be included in the council because the world has
changed. Most of the countries represented here today did not even
exist when the U.N. was formed, he added.
</P>
<P>
Cook also urged the U.N. finances to be put on a sound basis.
"It is not equitable that some members pay their contributions
while others do not. Britain pays in full and on time. Britain
expects every country, however large or however small, to do the
same," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the institutional reform, Security Council reform
and financial reform are critical to the U.N.'s future.
</P>
<P>
The British official also called on the international community
to continue the efforts to promote sustainable development,
prevent conflict and combat organized crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
