by Secretary-General Kofi Annan, said Tom Ikimi, foreign minister
of the Federal Republic of Nigeria, here today.
</P>
<P>
But the foreign minister stressed the outcome of the reform
should encompass and take on board the views and interests of all
member states.
</P>
<P>
He said the reform of the UN would be incomplete without a
corresponding reform of the Security Council. A reform of the
Security Council would entail a restructuring and expansion of its
membership in both categories to take account of the interested
membership of the organization and the need to reflect the
interests of all the constituent region.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said there was now abroad agreement on the
need for the expansion of membership of the Security Council in
both categories. With almost a third of the membership of the
United Nations, Africa should have adequate representation in an
expanded Security Council.
</P>
<P>
He said that at the 33rd Summit of the Organization of African
Unity held last June, leaders of Africa reaffirmed the need for
the region to have two permanent seats with full veto powers, and
Nigeria considered this demand legitimate and well deserved.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said there were conflict situations in
Africa which had threatened the security and stabilization and the
economic development of the region.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that urgent demands of socio-economic development
could not be effectively tackled without peace and stability, and
peace as well as stability in Africa would facilitate the
channeling of its limited resources into the critical areas of
political, social and economic development. 
