<HEADLINE> Drug Ring in Far West Indicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A newly unsealed grand
jury indictment in Sacramento, California, charges 16 men with
operating a drug ring in the Far West.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Attorney Paul Seave said the indictment accuses the
suspects of trafficking in methamphetamine, cocaine and marijuana
throughout the region, including Sacramento, the San Francisco Bay
Area, Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Alaska and Hawaii, The United Press
International reported today.
</P>
<P>
Seave said the key defendant in the case is 24-year-old Jason
David Hall of Sacramento, the alleged organizer of a drug
distribution network that has operated for five years.
</P>
<P>
Hall has been a fugitive since he was indicted on conspiracy
charges in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
Eight of the 16 defendants have pleaded guilty in the case, and
all of them face maximum sentences of life imprisonment if
convicted, with a mandatory minimum of not less than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The latest indictment alleges that Hall and seven others
operated a series of laboratories in San Bruno, Calif., Las Vegas
and Honolulu, to convert methamphetamine into crystal
methamphetamine, known on the street as ice. 
