<HEADLINE> Israeli Official Meets Ross on Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli official
held talks on Tuesday with U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis Ross
ahead of an Israeli-Palestinian meeting in Washington for a
possible solution of recent crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh told reporters after his
talks with Ross that they came to Washington to seek to "put the
peace process back on track."
</P>
<P>
Naveh will meet Palestinian officials here at the State
Department late this week.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian talks on peace process were deadlocked
since March when the Israeli government, violating peace accords
agreed both by Israel and the Palestinians, decided to build
Jewish housing units in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright took a trip to the Middle
East early this month, trying to re-vitalize the peace process,
and returned with nothing settled concerning the crisis.
</P>
<P>
But she has arranged for Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
and Palestinian negotiator Mahmoud Abbas to meet in New York next
week, hoping the two sides could re-open their peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Naveh, did not mention the real cause for the recent crisis in
the region, and what responsibility should be taken on the Israeli
side. He only blamed the Palestinian Authority for its slackening
of effort in fighting "terrorism."
</P>
<P>
"We don't see there are real results from (Palestinian leader
Yasser) Arafat's fight against terrorism. Since Secretary
Albright's trip there has been a deterioration in his efforts," he
complained.
</P>
<P>
Israeli diplomats in Washington said a joint U.S.-Israeli
committee on counter-terrorism would discuss the situation at
a meeting here on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
