<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Post Workers Protest against Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- About 10,000 employees of
Germany's state-run post company, the Deutsche Post AG, laid down
their jobs today in protest against a government plan to
liberalize the post services.
</P>
<P>
According to the German trade union for post workers DPG,
million of letters and parcels had not been delivered today across
Germany due to the protests. In many cities, counters of post
offices had also been kept closed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the liberalization plan proposed by German Post Minister
Wolfgang Boetsch, the Deutsche Post AG would only be able to
retain its monopoly of post deliveries of up to 100 gram until
2002. After that deadline, private operators would be allowed to
compete with the state-run company in all post services.
</P>
<P>
The trade union however fears that the initiative would lead to
about 10,000 job cuts.
</P>
<P>
Although the new post law is still under discussion in Bonn,
Boetsch said he was confident that it would be approved by the
German parliament within this year and would come into effect
on January 1, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
