<HEADLINE> Germany to See Strong Domestic Demand Next Year, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Expanding domestic demand would
replace exports as the primary driving force for Germany's
economic growth next year, a leading German economic research
institute predicted today.
</P>
<P>
In its latest economic report released today, the Kiel
Institute for World Economy predicted that Germany's gross
domestic product (GDP) would grow by 2.5 percent this year and 3.0
percent next year.
</P>
<P>
The economic upswing would also start to provide relief to the
job market, it said. On average, Germany's unemployment would be
about 100,000 less than the levels of this year and could be
reduced to 4.15 million by the end of December 1998, the report
said. 
</P>
