<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Reacts With "Abomination" to Massacres in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- France reacted to the latest
massacres in Algeria with "abomination" and the French society was
struck with horror on learning the massacre of more than 200
civilians in Bentalha south of Algiers Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Personalities from both the ruling Socialist Party and the
central-right UDF opposition party of France expressed their
feeling of horror over the massacre and said the international
community and the European Union should break their silence over
Algeria.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine today expressed his
"feeling of revulsion in front of the horrors suffered by the
Algerian people and a feeling of profound solidarity" toward the
Algerian people.
</P>
<P>
"After so many atrocities and intolerable crimes committed in
Algeria, this new act of barbarity greatly upset us and struck us
with horror," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves
Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
The latest killing in Bentalha is the second most bloody in
Algeria since 1992, after the massacre of 300 civilians in Sidi
Rais on August 29. The Algerian government gave much smaller
accounts of victims.
</P>
<P>
"In front of these tragic events, the French society expresses
its entire solidarity with the Algerian people. It reacts with
abomination to the violence and the terrorism which have plunged
Algeria into mourning," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Algerian people have the "legitimate right to
be protected," and repeated France's stand that the conflict in
Algeria should be solved through political means by Algerians
themselves.
</P>
<P>
On the latest announcement by the Islamic Salvation Army, the
armed wing of the Islamic Salvation Army, to start a cease-fire
with the government from October 1, the spokesman said that the
French government is yet to "study it."
</P>
<P>
The French government has been carrying out a "minimalist"
policy toward Algeria by refraining from making official comments
on the violence in the country, out of fear of terrorist attacks
in France.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said in a recent interview
with the daily Le Monde that "in the official field, the French
government is restrained in its expression" about Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The daily Le Figaro said that both the presidential advisors in
the Elysee Palace and the Foreign Ministry are strictly for a low
profile policy by France toward Algeria.
</P>
<P>
About 60 French nationals have been killed in Algeria since
1992 and the French capital of Paris and the central city of Lyon
were subjected to a wave of terrorist bombings in 1995, assumably
by Islamic extremists.
</P>
<P>
A French diplomat noted that the historical and close relations
between France and Algeria and the 600,000-strong Algerian
community in France call for a very careful policy by France.
</P>
<P>
Extreme-right National Front (FN) leader Jean-Marie Le Pen said
today that "Arab and Muslim countries are more qualified" to
interfere in Algeria than France, if there is a need to interfere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0063 </DOCNO>
