<HEADLINE> Time for India, Pakistan to Forget Past: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The time has come when
India and Pakistan should forget the past, sink their differences
and come to an agreement for lasting peace, the Press Trust of
India today quoted an Indian official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The money and energy being spent in both countries due to
continuous hostility could be saved and utilized for the welfare
of the people, India-held Jammu and Kashmir Chief Minister Farooq
Abdullah said on Tuesday while addressing a group of senior army
officers of the National Defense College in Srinagar.
</P>
<P>
The group, which also include officers of various countries,
are touring the country.
</P>
<P>
People of both countries have suffered immensely due to
hostility, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan have fought three wars since their
independence in 1947, of which two were over the disputed Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
However, the two countries have intensified their efforts to
solve their differences this year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of March, they resumed the foreign secretary-level
talks, which had been stalled for nearly three years, and three
rounds of talks have been held since then.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Indian and Pakistani foreign ministers held two
rounds of informal talks here in April and their prime ministers
also met for talks in May and September.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have expressed their determination to continue their
dialogue so as to normalize their ties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
