<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Car Makers Plan Production Boost in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Two Japanese automakers
plan to build additional factories in North America to increase
pressure on U.S. car manufacturers, The Wall Street Journal
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Toyota Motor Corp. and Honda Motor Co. each plan to build an
assembly plant in the United States or Canada but potential sites
were not disclosed, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Toyota also intends to double its capacity to 200,000 vehicles
a year at a truck factory still under construction in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
If the plans are realized, the Japanese automaker would be able
to produce 1.5 million cars and small trucks in the U.S. per year
early in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Toyota's capacity in the country had increased to about 785,000
vehicles annually by last year.
</P>
<P>
Honda, meanwhile, plans to increase production by about 100,000
vehicles a year, the Journal reported. Honda's capacity in North
America is now about 790,000.
</P>
<P>
The added production by both companies would make their
combined North American annual output about 2.5 million vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Toyota executives said they are simply responding to dealer
pressure for more cars. But a Honda spokesman denied claims by
sources who told the Journal about the company's North American
expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of this year, the share of Japanese
vehicles in the U.S. market increased to 23.9 percent from the
22.5 percent in the same period of last year. While the share of
the Big Three in the U.S. declined to 71.3 percent from 73.2
percent in the eight months of 1996, according to the auto
statistics released earlier this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
