<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rising Sea Levels Assessed on European Coastline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The European Union
publication European Report today issued an assessment report on
rising sea levels based on several European community research
projects.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that the rising sea levels are likely caused
by melting glaciers in the wake of global warming. It warned that
three Celsius degrees' up in the year of 2070 could result in an
average increase of 40 centimeters in sea levels.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to develop instruments for constant and
accurate monitoring of sea levels, the report claimed.
</P>
<P>
As many as 68 million Europeans living along the coastline may
be threatened by rising sea levels that go up at a rate of one to
1.5 millimeters a year.
</P>
<P>
Changes in sea levels are considered to exert tremendous
influences on the development of coastal areas in Europe,
particularly on regions where the social and economic
repercussions are likely to be most important. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
