<HEADLINE> Uganda is 8th Investment Choice in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is the eighth
investment destination country in Africa, The Monitor reported
today.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1997 world investment report on transnational
corporations, market structure and competition policy, Uganda
follows Nigeria, Egypt, Morocco, Tunisia, Angola, Ghana and
Azania.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investment flows into Africa reduced in 1996
from 1995 levels, except Nigeria where foreign investment
remained constant at 780 million U.S. dollars, and Angola, Gabon,
Zambia, Senegal, Cameroon and Mozambique where a notable
improvement was witnessed. Foreign direct investment to Uganda
stood at 140 million U.S. dollars in 1995, camparing with 120
million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investment into Uganda in 1992 was 3 million
U.S. dollars in 1992. 
