<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Steps Up Efforts to Cope With Haze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has stepped up
efforts to cope with the haze from forest fires raging in several
islands in the country, a senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The efforts include the evacuation of haze victims and the use
of information technology as well as meteorological and
geophysical data to help extinguish the fires, State Minister for
Environment Sarwono Kusumaatmadja said.
</P>
<P>
"Now it is not the time to blame each other. It is important to
realize that if we ignore environment-related information, the
consequences could be fatal," he said, referring to the disaster.
</P>
<P>
A prolonged drought and the slash-and-burn method used by many
plantation companies to open land have triggered forest fires in
Kalimantan, Sumatra, Irian Jaya, Bali and Sulawesi, producing the
haze that has already reached neighboring countries like Malaysia
and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Forestry Minister Djamaloedin Suryohadikusumo said Indonesia
has allocated funds amounting to 3.1 billion rupiah (1.07 million
U.S. dollars) and mobilized 8,437 skilled people for efforts to
put out the fires.
</P>
<P>
Data showed that more than 400,000 hectares of forest areas had
been destroyed in the fires between mid-August and September 19,
the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The government is using the satellites of the U.S. National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and the National Outerspace
and Aviation Agency in its effort to detect fire spots.
</P>
<P>
"The government has information on the location of fire spots
throughout Indonesia and we send it twice a day to all provinces
so that the local governments could act quickly to extinguish the
fires," an official of the Environmental Impact Management Agency,
Gempur Adnan, said.
</P>
<P>
Minister Sarwono further said other preventive measures could
be the evacuation of people to safer areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, there have been offers of assistance from
abroad in combating the haze.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,200 Malaysian firefighters and paramedics arrived
in separate locations Tuesday in Riau, Jambi, South Sumatra, East
Kalimantan and West Kalimantan provinces to join their Indonesian
counterparts in fighting the raging fires.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said the haze has exposed 20 million people to
the danger of respiratory problems in the country and in Malaysia
and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Two persons have already died of respiratory ailments blamed on
the haze.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
