<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indigenisation Urged to Reduce Poverty in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean minister of
state today underscored the need to use the indigenisation of the
economy as an effective tool of reducing poverty in the country.
</P>
<P>
Cephas Msipa, state Enterprises and Indigenisation Minister,
said economic empowerment of the majority should be treated as a
national program to improve the lives of people who were
discriminated on racial grounds by previous colonial governments.
</P>
<P>
"Indigenisation is a crucial and indeed an almost
indispensable aspect in poverty reduction in Zimbabwe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Msipa was addressing more than 50 participants here at an
indigenisation and poverty reduction seminar organised by the
Zimbabwe Institute of Development Studies.
</P>
<P>
Increased economic growth through the creation of more
enterprises would translate into more national income which, if
distributed equally, would be key in poverty reduction, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Let us all dedicate ourselves to pursue all strategies that
will result not only in the reduction but elimination of poverty
in Zimbabwe," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, poverty was very high in both rural
and urban areas, a situation "politically and socially
unacceptable particularly in a country which is endowed with an
abundance of resources."
</P>
<P>
Msipa noted that efforts by entrepreneurs in the informal
sector to break into big business were hampered by reasons
ranging from financial to restrictive laws and by-laws.
</P>
<P>
The government was promoting other initiatives such as
affirmative action in its procurement of goods and services,
sub-contracting and employee stock ownership plans, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister said these programs should be aided by
easy access to information for people intending to start
businesses.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the government, in conjunction with other
business organisations, was considering establishing business
information centers in all major towns and rural centers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
