<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier, Kazakh President Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng and
Kazakh President Nursultan Abishevich Nazarbayev held talks here
today, pledging joint efforts in furthering bilateral relations,
particularly economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is here on a working visit, said the success of China
National Petroleum Corporation in the bid in two petroleum
projects in Kazakhstan marks the start of major economic and trade
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
As long as the two countries work closely together, their
cooperation in petroleum sector can make progress and set an
example for the cooperation on the basis of equality and mutual
benefit.
</P>
<P>
Li and Nazarbayev expressed satisfaction over the "smooth
development" of bilateral relations since the two countries
established diplomatic ties five years ago, saying that such
relations have entered a "brand new period" and seen "immense
potentials."
</P>
<P>
Li said the two countries have had frequent exchanges and
cooperation in all areas and maintained the exchange of high-level
visits, thus increasing mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
China and Kazakhstan signed several documents including a joint
declaration, an agreement on confidence-building in the military
field and an agreement on disarmament in the past years, Li said.
</P>
<P>
These documents demonstrate the friendly relations between the
two nations, Li said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two countries can use their geographical and
mutually-supplementary advantages to gradually raise their
economic cooperation to a high level.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev said Kazakhstan highly values the visit of Premier
Li. He described the oil agreement signed by the two countries as
a "cross-century" document which is of "great importance" to the
development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev also extended congratulations on the smooth return
of Hong Kong and the successful convening of the 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing was present at the talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
