<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Nations Favor Gradual Capital Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from
developing countries today called on the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) to adopt a manner of gradual progress in promoting the
liberalization of capital movement so as to prevent possible
financial crises in these countries.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Massad, governor of the Fund for Chile, told the World
Bank /IMF Annual Meetings here that the representatives of the
Latin American countries had clearly expressed their willingness
to extend the IMF's mandate to enable it to promote liberalization
 of capital accounts in its member countries.
</P>
<P>
But Massad quickly added that precipitate liberalization would
create new financial crises with a spillover to other countries
resulting from the contagion effect.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement adopted by the Interim Committee of
the IMF on September 21, the jurisdiction of the IMF was extended
to enable it to promote the liberalization of capital movement.
</P>
<P>
One of the most important aspects of the future regime is the
treatment of prudential measures, Massad said.
</P>
<P>
"Owing to the structural characteristics of the economies of
our region -- mostly small open economies requiring external
resources and with insufficiently diversified exports -- they are
highly vulnerable to external shocks," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the meetings, an Egyptian representative, on behalf of the
Arab countries, said the recent financial problems in many
emerging markets are largely the result of the increased
globalization of these markets.
</P>
<P>
In order to obtain the maximum benefit from globalization and
to minimize its negative effects, many developing countries have
implemented a series of sound economic reforms, accompanied by
comprehensive structural reforms, said Atef Ebeid, the Egyptian
privatization minister.
</P>
<P>
But these measures alone are not sufficient, as recent
developments in Southeast Asia have shown, he added.
</P>
<P>
Even countries that follow sound economic policies are not safe
from effects of financial disturbances in the region, Ebeid said.
</P>
<P>
It is important for the IMF and World Bank to provide technical
assistance to developing countries to support their efforts aimed
at integrating themselves into the new world order, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
