<HEADLINE> Malaysian Aircraft to Help Put Out Indonesian Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government
has decided to send Royal Malaysian Air Force (RMAF) aircraft such
as "Charlie" to help put out the fires in Indonesia, a Malaysian
official said today.
</P>
<P>
National Disaster Relief Management Committee Chairman Mohamed
Rahmat said the RMAF had been informed of this duty and the
aircraft would be sent immediately.
</P>
<P>
"The aircraft will be equipped with the necessary equipment to
enable them to release water from the air on the burning areas,"
he was quoted by the Malaysian national news agency Bernama as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,200 Malaysian firefighters are already in Sumatra of
Indonesia to help extinguish the forest fires which have resulted
in thick haze affecting neighboring Malaysia, Singapore, Brunei
and now the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed said more firefighting personnel would leave for
Pontianak and Balikpapan in Kalimantan early next week.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's efforts to help Indonesia control its forest fires
has received the support of nine companies involved in land
development in Sumatra and Kalimantan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Due to the haze, the air quality over the Malaysian city of
Kuching on the Kalimantan Island remained far above the hazardous
level today while elsewhere in the country it was at very
unhealthy or unhealthy levels, according to a statement by the
Environment Department.  
</P>
</TEXT>
