<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Able to Locate All Air Violations: Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran's lookouts are now fully
prepared to identify and locate enemy aircraft even if they fly at
low altitude and blind spots, an officer said today.
</P>
<P>
Qasem Rahimian, head of the State Air Observation, told the
press that lookouts have been stationed at blind spots, where
aircraft can not be detected on radar, to check low-level air
operations of enemies.
</P>
<P>
Rahimian, an officer in charge of the observation post at
Zulfaqar region, about 150 kilometers south of Tehran, said that
such observation posts should be permanently stationed along
border areas where natural barriers prevent radar from detecting
and locating aircraft.
</P>
<P>
He said that vessel traveling, air flights and launching of
long-range missiles of the enemy were detected by the lookouts
during the 1980-1988 Iran-Iraq War.
</P>
<P>
The officer also underlined the need for collaboration of
academic centers, adding that mutual cooperation could pave the
way for improving the operations of observation, radar and air
defense systems.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the English language daily Tehran Times today
commented that the maneuvers being held in the Zulfaqar area aims
to keep the effectiveness of the Iranian armed forces as high
as possible.
</P>
<P>
It noted that enhancing Iranian army combat readiness should
not be seen as a threat to Iran's friends and neighbors, adding
that "Iran will never be the first country to fire the first
bullet toward its neighbors, but will always be ready to face the
aggressors with an Iron fist."
</P>
<P>
The maneuvers held by the Iranian army, together with Iranian
naval and air forces in the Gulf and Caspian Sea are in honor of
the Defense Week starting from September 22, which commemorates
the Iran-Iraq War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
