<HEADLINE> Australia Asks HK to Investigate Hazardous Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government
today said it has called on Hong Kong authorities to investigate
three containers of potentially hazardous Australian computer
scrap seized by Hong Kong customs.
</P>
<P>
The government has asked Hong Kong's Environmental Protection
Department to examine the containers allegedly shipped from Sydney
without a permit, a spokesman for Environment Minister Robert Hill
said.
</P>
<P>
Environment watchdog Greenpeace claimed that HiTechnology Metal
Recyclers (HMR) exported the scrap aboard the freighter Zim Sydney
on September 12, the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The shipment showed that Australia was still dumping hazardous
material on developing countries despite insisting that stringent
laws had stopped the practice, Greenpeace charged.
</P>
<P>
It said the scrap contained lead cadmium, barium, mercury and
polychlorinated bophenyls (PCBs).
</P>
<P>
But HMR Assistant Manager Guy Channery denied his company had
shipped the load to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that HMR had sold some "material" to another
company, which he refused to name and which he said had shipped
the material overseas to a "destination we don't know."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the government had not yet been notified by
Hong Kong as to whether the load was hazardous.  
</P>
</TEXT>
