<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Russia's First Deputy Prime
 Minister Anatoly Chubais said here today that Russia's economic
situation has begun to improve, and called for more foreign
investments.
</P>
<P>
The country's financial market remains stable and very strong,
Chubais told a news conference at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center this evening.
</P>
<P>
"We estimate that the (economic) situation has begun to
improve" for the first time in almost ten years, he said, stating
that this year Russia's inflation rate is expected to be reduced
to about 13 percent and next year, 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chubais stressed that his country welcomes a flow of long-term
capital to be started in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Russia has gold-currency reserves of about 800 million
U.S. dollars, and the Russian government is capable of controlling
the currency's exchange rate, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between Russia and the World Bank and the IMF has
improved significantly with good prospects, he stated.
</P>
<P>
"We are satisfied with the IMF-World Bank interaction in the
area of structural reforms," he said, adding that the cooperation
"helps to restore economic growth and to maintain macroeconomic
stability" in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recent financial turmoil in Southeast Asia,
Russian Central Bank Chief Sergei Dubinin stressed the need at the
 news conference for every country to enhance its own financial
system.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia is eager to strengthen its control over the
 macroeconomic policy.
</P>
<P>
During the ongoing WB/IMF annual meetings in Hong Kong, the
Russian delegates have signed with representatives of other
countries a number of agreements on cooperation in the banking
sector, he revealed.  
</P>
