<HEADLINE> ADB Provides Two Loans to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) today approved two loans with a total sum of 256 million
U.S. dollars to finance a water shortage alleviation and an air
pollution reduction project respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release of the Manila-based bank, 100
million U.S. dollars of the loans are to be used in a water supply
project in Wenzhou Prefecture in Zhejiang Province, East China.
</P>
<P>
The project will provide good-quality raw water for treatment
and distribution and will increase levels of irrigation water and
flood protection for the rural communities surrounding the
reservoir site.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 156 million dollars are to finance the
improvement of the environment in Xi'an, Xianyang and Tongchuan
cities in Shaanxi Province, Northwest China.
</P>
<P>
The project will cut down air pollution, conserve energy,
promote the use of cleaner fuel, strengthen environmental
management agencies and continue moves toward market-based energy
pricing.
</P>
<P>
It would also help replace old and inefficient boilers and
domestic stoves with modern, efficient cogeneration plants and
district heating systems; substitute natural gas for coal burning;
and reduce emissions from a large cement plant in Tongchuan.
</P>
<P>
The ADB will also provide a technical assistance grant of
935,000 U.S. dollars to strengthen the capability of the Shaanxi
Provincial Planning Commission and the Shaanxi Environmental
Protection Bureau to plan and implement environmental improvement
projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
