<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Uganda Becomes No. One Coffee Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has surpassed Cote
d'Ivoire to become Africa's leading coffee producer, harvesting
about 4.2 million bags (60 kilos per bag) of coffee in the
1996/97 season.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Managing Director of the Uganda Coffee
Development Authority (UCDA) T.N. Bucyanayandi here on Tuesday
while briefing the Parliamentary Committee on Trade and Industry
about the coffee sector in relation to the national budget.
</P>
<P>
And this (1996/97 coffee season) is the second year that
Uganda exports over 4 million bags of coffee, he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 4.15 million bags were exported in 1995/96 coffee
season, compared to 2.79 million bags in the previous year, he
added.
</P>
<P>
With last year's production, Uganda took the lead from Cote
d'Ivoire which produced 2.7 million bags in 1995/96 and about 3.7
million bags this coffee season.
</P>
<P>
Coffee has been Uganda's biggest foreign exchange earner
covering 65 percent of the country's export income.
</P>
<P>
The significant rise of coffee production or exports in recent
years is attributed to a number of measures taken by the Ugandan
government in a bid to promote its coffee production.
</P>
<P>
The government has set up three task forces to review coffee
production, marketing and export systems, and based on their
recommendations, the UCDA has revised its relevant regulations
concerning coffee production and export so as to make them more
responsive to coffee industry.
</P>
<P>
Privatization of the coffee nurseries has been initiated to
increase the production of coffee seedlings so as to speed up
replacement of low yielding coffee trees at reasonable costs to
farmers.
</P>
<P>
With the introduction of the prolific clonal coffee, Uganda's
coffee production has increased by a wide margin. The clonal
coffee has an yielding capacity of three tons per hectare
compared to the robusta coffee with an yield of 1.2 tons per
hectare.
</P>
<P>
The coffee retention system introduced by the world's coffee
producing countries in October 1993 and the liberalization of
export system have also contributed to the sharp rise of coffee
earnings in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The retention system has helped the rise of coffee price from
84 U.S. Cents to 2 Dollars per kilogram since African coffee
producers adopted in August 1993 a new policy which stipulates a
20 percent reduction of coffee exports.
</P>
<P>
Liberalization of the export system has removed export
monopoly of the Coffee Marketing Board Ltd. and over 80 companies
in the country have been licensed to export coffee.
</P>
<P>
As a result, farmers in Uganda can earn between 60 percent and
70 percent of the world price, or about 1.4 Dollars per kilogram
from a mere 20 percent before liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The Uganda Coffee Farmers' Association has decided to double
the country's current annual coffee production of 4.2 million
bags during the years 1996-2001 and introduce appropriate
measures to this end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Free Capital Flow, No Blame for Currency Crisis: Singapore Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's Finance
Minister Richard Hu said here today that the flow of capital
should not be blamed for the recent currency turbulence in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
"The greatest lesson Asia can learn from the financial turmoil
is the opening up of the world capital market," said Hu, who is
here attending the 1997 Annual Meetings of the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center today, the Singaporean official said: "There are
pluses and minors in opening the capital market."
</P>
<P>
The negative side is volatility while the positive picture is
the inflow of foreign investment, explained Hu, who has been
working in the Finance Ministry for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
"The solution is not to close the markets completely," he said,
adding that the way-out is how to use the money efficiently to
generate income.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Thailand, which was hit hardest in the Southeast
Asia currency crisis, Hu said: "Don't blame entirely on the
capital market. The capital market allowed this (crisis) to
happen, but if you cut it off, you also cut off the advantages."
</P>
<P>
In his view, the reason behind the collapse of the Thai
currency market is that all the economic fundamentals became weak
at the same time -- declining export competitiveness, large
current account deficit, insufficient infrastructure, too much
short-term external loans being put into unproductive projects.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has launched a rescue package of 17.2 billion U.S.
dollars to bail out the beleaguered Thai economy. "It is a
question of restoring the fundamentals," said Hu.
</P>
<P>
The Singaporean minister did not think that the currency
turmoil would put an end to the "Asia Miracle", a term
describing the region's up to ten percent annual GDP growth over
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian fundamentals have not changed. The trouble is that
they have been going a little fast without slowing down to provide
the infrastructure which is necessary to sustain long growth," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Asia has natural resources, well-educated labor, high savings,
market-oriented and opening policies, and all it needs is a good
and necessary pause to regain strength, he went on. "This slowdown
in fact may be good for Asia." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
