<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Weather Currency Storm Sooner: Ramos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos
expressed confidence here today that the Philippines will weather
sooner than expected the currency turbulence which swept across
Southeast Asia for the last few months.
</P>
<P>
The country not only continued to attract investors, but also
retained businessmen's confidence in the country's economy despite
the devaluation of the peso in the last few months, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
According to a report to the president, investments in the
country reached 587.9 billion pesos (18.4 billion U.S. dollars) in
the first eight months this year, exceeding the 550 billion peso
(about 17 billion dollars) target for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
The revenue of the export sector soared to 13.77 billion
dollars from January to July this year with an average growth rate
of 22.1 percent per month, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Buoyed by the positive developments in the economy, especially
the continuing influx of investments and the satisfactory
performance of exports, Ramos said the country would soon weather
the currency woes also hitting Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia and
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The value of the peso has fallen by 28 percent to the present
level of 33.63 pesos to one U.S. dollar since the central bank
allowed the currency to float within a wider band on July 11.
</P>
<P>
To cushion the impact of the currency meltdown, Ramos today
created a special task force to undertake consultations.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the creation of the task force was only one of the
many issues discussed at a cabinet meeting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Other decisions reached by the cabinet included: to reduce the
current account deficit, to ensure a balanced monetary and
exchange rate policy, to continue prudent fiscal management and to
close the gap between private savings and investments, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
