<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developed Nations Urged to Increase Aid to Developing World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries today
urged the industrialized nations to honor their commitment to
increase official development assistance (ODA) to the developing
world.
</P>
<P>
"We deeply regret the steady decline in official development
assistance," Ethiopian Finance Minister Sufian Ahmed told the
annual meetings of the World Bank and International Monetary Fund
(IMF).
</P>
<P>
"This decline makes it difficult for our countries to
successfully complete the ambitious reform programs being
implemented in the priority areas of our economies," he added.
</P>
<P>
At the meetings, Pakistan also expressed its concern about the
sharp decline in the net official flows to developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz said it was unfortunate
the ODA target of 0.7 percent of GNP set some two decades ago
remains a far cry and that in case of many donor countries there
is a persistent decline in their share of GNP devoted to
assistance to developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Private capital flows are no substitute for concessional
assistance because the former are directed towards profitable
commercial ventures in fast growing economies, while the latter is
needed for building human capital and for alleviating poverty in a
large number of low-income nations, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Quality growth can not be achieved and sustained without more
rapid progress in social sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim said that it is
disturbing to note that ODA to developing countries continues to
decline despite evidence of rising poverty in many countries.
</P>
<P>
"I therefore urge donor countries to renew their commitment to
ODA through a smart partnership between donors and recipients," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Group of 24 composed of developing countries said in a
communique issued here that the percentage of ODA of the GNP in
the developed countries had been in steady decline over the past
50 years and hit its nadir last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the amount of ODA dropped to 41 billion U.S. dollars,
a reduction of 20.7 percent compared with the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
