<HEADLINE> Okinawa Officials Criticize New Japan-U.S. Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Government officials in Japan's
Okinawa Prefecture criticized today the new guidelines for
Japan-U.S. defence cooperation and demanded a reduction of the
U.S. bases in the island, Kyodo reported.
</P>
<P>
There are fears about the effect of the U.S. use of the
prefecture's air and sea ports on the economic activities and
people's life and property in the prefecture, Okinawa Governor
Mashihide Ota said.
</P>
<P>
Under the new guidelines, Japan will allow the U.S. military
forces to use its civilian air and sea ports in case of emergency
near Japan.
</P>
<P>
Ota made it clear that he will continue asking Washington to
restructure and reduce the bases, and to prevent them from being
made permanent.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Naha Mayor Kosei Oyadomari said that the
inclusion of Naha, capital of Okinawa, in the list of civilian
facilities to be used by the U.S, forces, had shocked his city.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa Mayor Shusei Arakawa said the review of the 1978
guidelines for Japan-U.S. defence cooperation was in effect a
review of the Japan-U.S. security treaty, which not only secures
the continued presence of the U.S. bases but also "leads to a
substantial strengthening of the bases of Japan's Self-Defense
Forces."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, "It is necessary to have a national debate
on the guidelines."
</P>
<P>
The new guidelines, issued in New York on Tuesday, have spurred
wide criticism from the Japanese opposition.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
