<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Aussie Ministers Quit Over Travel Allowance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian federal
government today plunged into its deepest crisis with two key
ministers forced to resign over revelations about travel allowance
claims.
</P>
<P>
Transport Minister John Sharp and Administrative Services
Minister David Jull resigned less than 24 hours after it was made
public that Sharp had secretly paid back 6,292 U.S. dollars in
questionable claims.
</P>
<P>
Sharp, who repaid the money after voluntarily correcting his
claims for travel allowance, said he quit to avoid embarrassing
and distracting the government.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "I believe there was no impropriety."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard, who accepted their resignations,
ordered an urgent inquiry into Sharp's claims and Jull's
no-questions-asked acceptance of the repayment when details of
claims were about to be tabled in the parliament in May, the
Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he acted swiftly, after first learning
of the issue last weekend, to uphold the high standards he
promised at the last election.
</P>
<P>
Howard said he had no alternative, even though he did not
believe the two men acted improperly or dishonestly.
</P>
<P>
The resignations have brought to six the number of ministers
and parliamentary secretaries forced to quit under a cloud since
the Howard government won office in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
Records show that in 1994 and 1995 Sharp consistently claimed
travel allowance for staying in Canberra on Sunday and Thursday
nights at the start and end of parliamentary sessions.
</P>
<P>
Most of the repaid claims for 1996 were also for Sunday and
Thursday nights, with Sharp admitting that he could not be sure
whether he was actually at home.
</P>
<P>
Two other ministers were also revealed today to have repaid
some travel allowance claims after records were made public in
May, AAP said.
</P>
<P>
Veterans Affairs Minister Bruce Scott has repaid 1,234 U.S.
dollars and Science Minister Peter McGaruan 4,550 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he was satisfied with the explanations
from the two ministers.
</P>
<P>
Three former government ministers -- Geoff Prosser, Jim Short
and Brian Gibson -- have been forced to resign over the past 18
months, all falling foul of conflicts between private interest and
public duty. There was no suggestion of impropriety.
</P>
<P>
Senator Mal Colston was also forced to quit as deputy president
of the Senate earlier this year for the same reason.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
