<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA Decide on New Arbitration Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- European soccer's governing
body UEFA voted unanimously on Wednesday for some of its disputes
to be decided by a Swiss-based arbitration panel to keep them out
of the jurisdiction of the civil courts.
</P>
<P>
In a major departure from the past, delegates from UEFA's
51-member countries agreed at their eighth Extraordinary Congress
here that non-sporting disputes should be settled by the Court of
Arbitration for Sport (CAS), based in Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
Executive Committee member Dr Joseph Mifsud of Malta said the
arbitration panel would not deal with sporting disputes but with
issues such as doping, club suspensions or fines and other matters
of a pecuniary nature.
</P>
<P>
"If it is a dispute of a sporting nature like whether a red
card or player's suspension is valid or not, then we shall deal
with it through our own disciplinary procedures as before," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"But where there is a dispute of a pecuniary matter, or of a
doping case which cannot be resolved by UEFA, then the appellant
can take the case to CAS who will take the final decision, " he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
