<HEADLINE> Former Yamaichi President Nabbed in Payoff Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo prosecutors today
arrested Atsuo Miki, former president of Yamaichi Securities Co.,
in connection with the brokerage's alleged payoffs of some 79
million yen (660,000 U.S. dollars) to a corporate racketeer.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo District Public Prosecutors Office suspects that Miki
approved illegal compensations to the suspected racketeer Ryuichi
Koike for securities trading losses, in violation of the
Commercials Code and the Securities and Exchange Law.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors today searched Miki's home and his Yamaichi
Securities head office.
</P>
<P>
Five former and current executives of the brokerage house were
already arrested in connection with the case on September 17.
</P>
<P>
Miki, who resigned as president of Yamaichi in August over the
scandal, is suspected of planning the illegal compensations
together with other executives.
</P>
<P>
Koike, who is in custody and has been indicted in similar
payoff scandals involving Nomura Securities Co., and Dai-Ichi
Kangyo Bank, was served a fresh arrest warrant September 17 in
connection with the case.
</P>
<P>
According to investigation sources, Koike opened an account at
Yamaichi in June 1994 through a real estate company owned by his
younger brother and asked the brokerage to undertake illegal
discretionary trading on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
He demanded compensation from Yamaichi in December the same
year after the discretionary trading resulted in losses totaling
some 30 million yen (250,000 U.S. dollars)
</P>
<P>
Yamaichi reimbursed Koike for the losses with the use of
profits garnered through investments on futures trading on the
Singapore International Money Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Payoff to Sokaiya are banned under Japan's Commercial Code,
while both the reimbursement of stock transaction losses and
discretionary securities trading are prohibited under the
Securities and Exchange Law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
