<HEADLINE> French Fashion Designer Sees Expanding Chinese Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Fashion designer Daniel
Tribouillard, who is here as a guest of the Shanghai International
Fashion and Culture Festival, said here today that he would like
to present the charm of Chinese culture to the rest of the world
through his work.
</P>
<P>
He added that he is confident about his business in China.
</P>
<P>
This is Tribouillard's fifth visit to China's largest
commercial center.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the oriental sentiments that permeate his work
have contributed to the designer's success. Evidence of the
architecture of Beijing's Forbidden City, the designs of blue
porcelain, the frog buttons of traditional Chinese gowns, and
flowers like the chrysanthemum, plum blossom, and cymbidium can be
found in his designs. He has even used Chinese folk songs as
background music for some of his fashion shows.
</P>
<P>
"There is so much to be learned from Chinese culture. It has
fascinated me and every now and then gives me inspirations,"
Tribouillard commented.
</P>
<P>
He has brought about 100 items that caused quite a stir in
Paris last April with him to this festival, whose theme is "Best
Wishes to China" His work reflects oriental refinement and
elegance while retaining modern elements and advanced design
techniques.
</P>
<P>
The audience are touched, he said, because they see their own
tradition and culture in it.
</P>
<P>
He opened his first shop in Shanghai two years ago and now has
high hopes for the Chinese market, and says that his company,
Lenonard, will focus on Asia, as the demand for fashion increases
with the standard of living.
</P>
<P>
"I'd like to let Asian people, especially the Chinese people,
know that Leonard's designers can make them look more beautiful,"
he explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
