<HEADLINE> World Bank Backed Agriculture Project in Heilongjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A new agriculture development
project, backed by the World Bank, began to be undertaken today in
Heilongjiang Province in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
The 240-million-US-dollar project is one of the largest in the
country, according to Yu Fei, director of the Provincial
Agricultural Development World Bank Loan office. Half of the funds
will come from the World Bank, and the rest from local governments.
</P>
<P>
It has some 80 sub-projects in animal husbandry, aquatic
products breeding, and farm products processing, in 31 counties
and cities, and is expected to be completed in five years.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture says that 7.74 billion dollars of
the 28 billion dollars in loans the World Bank has extended to
China are in agriculture development. The bank has backed 184
projects in the country.
</P>
<P>
After a careful study of the province, John Stemp, World Bank
project manager, said that the province is rich in agricultural
resources, with its vast stretches of grassland and inland waters.
</P>
<P>
"The project is aimed at improving the overall economic
efficiency of agricultural development by increasing the output of
animal husbandry and aquatic products industry and importing new
technology and equipment to process farm products," Stemp noted.
</P>
<P>
Sun Kuiwen, vice-governor of the province, said the province
produces 30 billion kilograms of grain annually, more than 60
percent of which is sold directly at market, and the project will
bring in more profits by introducing advanced food processing
equipment and technology.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that the project can bring total output of 25
billion yuan and 5.4 billion yuan in profits over the next
decade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
