<HEADLINE> Ramos Calls for Respect for Court's Ruling on PIRMA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos today
called on the Filipinos to respect the Supreme Court decision on a
people's initiative to amend the country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
In a statement he read at his weekly press conference in the
Presidential Palace, Ramos said he viewed the court's decision as
a "clear verdict that citizens can not avail of the people's
initiative as a means to effect changes in our constitution at
this time because of the inadequacy of the law."
</P>
<P>
"I called on everyone to respect the High Court's decision just
as I welcome the announcement of the pro-people's initiative
group, the People's Initiative for Reform, Modernization and
Action (PIRMA), to abide and be guided by it," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court junked the third petition filed by the PIRMA
to change the charter in a vote of 13:0 on Tuesday, effectively
ending a campaign by Ramos' supporters to have him run for a
second term.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the ruling should lay to rest "any remaining
unfounded speculations about my own position" on the matter of
charter changes as categorically enunciated in his recent
statements.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the president has made it clear that he would not seek
a second term and that changes to the charter can only be made
after the May 1998 elections by the way of a constitutional
convention.
</P>
<P>
In the past few months, charter change moves seeking to extend
the term of President Ramos has caused political uncertainties in
the country, prompting half a million people to attend a protest
rally held in Manila on September 21.
</P>
<P>
The country's constitution allows Ramos to serve only a single
term of six years. As required by the charter, Ramos should step
down when his term ends in June next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
