<HEADLINE> S. Korean President Resigns as Ruling Party Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 24 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam formally resigned as head of the ruling New Korea Party
(NKP) today, paving the way for party presidential candidate Lee
Hoi-chang to take the helm of the troubled party.
</P>
<P>
Kim submitted his resignation to the NKP head office via his
senior secretary for political affairs Cho Hong-rae this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Lee is expected to become party leader in a national convention
to be held September 30, with Kim as an honorary president of the
party.
</P>
<P>
Cho said Kim asked his party members to be united in their
support for Lee.
</P>
<P>
The practice of handing over party presidency is aimed at
bolstering the political power of the presidential candidate
before the December presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Lee's candidacy is facing a grave crisis due to his low public
support and intraparty conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Some critics within the NKP openly demand the replacement of
Lee's candidacy and members of a NKP faction loyal to Kim are
threatening that they may "take group action" unless Lee's
popularity rebounds soon.
</P>
<P>
Lee is now in the third place trailing opposition leader Kim
Dae-jung and Rhee In-je, former Kyonggi governor, in the
presidential campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
