<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Urban Families not Richer in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli's urban
wage-earning families' average net monthly income in 1996 remained
virtually the same as in the previous year, Israeli Central Bureau
of Statistics (CBS) announced today.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the monthly income averaged 7,200 shekels (about 2,050
U.S. dollars), which in reality was equal to that of 1995 by
taking inflation into consideration.
</P>
<P>
With inflation rate at 10 percent in 1996, the averaged net
monthly income of 6,527 shekel (about 1,865 dollars) in 1995 had
no real increase in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The CBS said the data was based on a survey of 4,581
wage-earning households. Further details of the study are to be
released in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
Gross monthly income of these families last year averaged 9,250
shekels (about 2,643 dollars), before deductions for income tax,
National Insurance Institute payments and health tax.
</P>
<P>
This figure was 0.1 percent lower in real term than the 1995's
8,417 shekels (about 2,405 dollars) considering inflation rate,
the CBS said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
