<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Well Curbed in Brazil: Finance Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The expected rate of
inflation for the year 1997 is between five and six percent, the
lowest Brazil has seen since the early 1950's, Brazilian Finance
Minister Pedro Malan said here today.
</P>
<P>
This year will be the fourth consecutive year of declining
inflation since 1993, a most important achievement of Brazilian
society in recent years, he told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the country's inflation stood at nine to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Curbed inflation has laid foundation for achieving the other
two macro-economic objectives of the Brazilian government --
sustained growth and more social justice, said Malan, who is here
attending the annual meetings of the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The year 1997 will also be the fifth consecutive year of
sustained growth of per capita GDP of Brazil, he said. The average
growth rate in the past five years is over four percent in real
terms.
</P>
<P>
But Brazil's economy would grow faster as favorable conditions
are created through privatization, productivity increases and
investment in education, he said.
</P>
<P>
Millions of Brazilians had been lifted out of poverty, but much
more remains to be done in the area which requires a medium- and
long-term view, he said.
</P>
<P>
There are two major challenges facing Brazilian macroeconomic
policy -- the current account deficit and public sector deficit,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's current account deficit rose from 2.5 percent of GDP
in 1995 to 3.3 percent last year, and to 4.3 percent in the 12
months ending on August 31, he said.
</P>
<P>
But about half of the current account deficit has been financed
by foreign direct investment in 1997, he noted. Brazil will
continue to tap the international capital market by issuing
longer-maturity instruments, he said.
</P>
<P>
In order to further bring down the public sector deficit, which
has dropped to five percent of GDP, he said, fiscal reforms and a
tight budget will be adopted.
</P>
<P>
The Federal government has entered into legally binding
agreements with 20 of the 27 states on their fiscal adjustment and
privatization programs for the next few years, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aboriginal Health National Shame for Australia: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The health status of
Australia's indigenous people is a national shame, a leading
medical adviser told the World Health Organization's Western
Pacific Committee meeting in Sydney today.
</P>
<P>
Aboriginal infant mortality rate is about three times higher
than that of non-indigenous Australian infants and life expectancy
of Australia's 300,000 Aboriginal men and women are 15 to 20 years
below that of non-indigenous Australians, Dr. Ian Anderson told
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Anderson, a medical adviser to a governmental agency in charge
of Aboriginal health services, told delegates from more than 30
countries that blindness occurs up to 10 times more frequently in
Aboriginal and Torres Strait Island people than among other
Australians.
</P>
<P>
A 1994 study showed one-third of indigenous Australians
suffered from a long-term health condition, Anderson was quoted
today by the Australian Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Anderson noted that the effects of substance abuse,
particularly alcohol and tobacco, malnutrition and poor child
health are typical conditions facing indigenous Australians, who
live 20 years less on average than non-indigenous people.
</P>
<P>
"High unemployment, a lack of adequate housing and community
structure particularly in remote rural areas of Australia,
compound the disadvantages of indigenous people that contribute to
... (their lower) health status."
</P>
<P>
"Quite bluntly the lower status of indigenous people,
especially if you compare it to the wider Australian community, is
a matter of national shame," Anderson said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
