<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some 190 Iranians Drowned in Caspian Sea in Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Parviz Fallah, head of the Public Relations Department of the
Mazanderan Provincial Law Enforcement Forces, was quoted by the
agency as saying that a few of them were drowned in the rivers in
the province.
</P>
<P>
The official said that most of the victims were visitors who
were not familiar with swimming or had ventured to swim in
prohibited areas.
</P>
<P>
He said statistics show that the youngest drowned was
two-year-old and the oldest 57.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a total of 252 people were drowned in the Caspian
Sea and the rivers in Mazanderan province. The death toll stood
at 287 in the previous Summer.
</P>
<P>
Some local people attributed the high death toll to the
separation of women and men in the swimming areas due to the
Islamic code.
</P>
<P>
Every year in summer hundreds of thousands of tourists,
particularly from the capital of Tehran, go to the Caspian
Sea coastal areas for a relief in the summer resorts.
</P>
<P>
However, the Islamic law prohibits men and women from
swimming together not only in the swimming pools but also in
the sea no matter they are married or unmarried, old or
young.
</P>
<P>
Armed policemen even patrol along the beach. Those who
swim together regardless of sex should be put into jail and
be punished. Thus, a couple and a family have to swim in
different and distant zones without protection by their friends
and other experienced swimmers.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the female can not swim with the swimsuit, they
have to go into the sea with long clothes covering the whole
body. This is also one of the causes for high death toll of the
sea-going tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
