<HEADLINE> State Owned Enterprises Privatized in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Privatization Board (PB) of
Bangladesh has so far completed the process of privatizing 32
State-Owned Enterprises (SOEs) since the present government came
to power in June 23 last year, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
Of the 32, PB Chairman Kazi Zafarullah said, three industries
had already been handed over to new owners, letter of intent for
six had been issued and 20 would be put on sale immediately.
</P>
<P>
He added that three out of the 32 SOEs could not be handed over
on the order of the court despite payment by new owners.
</P>
<P>
The PB had identified 54 SOEs to divest in the current fiscal
year (starting from July 1, 1997), he stated.
</P>
<P>
The PB chairman urged donors' representatives to come forward
with financial assistance so that the government could pay the
proper dues of the workers, arrange retraining program for wishful
workers and bear the long-term liabilities of the privatizing
companies.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said that the PB off-loaded government shares in
nine companies since he assumed the office five years ago.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that five SOEs would be put under the management
of the workers and employees of the respective industries on trial
basis at the instruction of the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The PB was now holding talks with the labor leaders and
identifying five factories, he said, adding that the government
was very much conscious about the protection of interest of
workers of privatizing SOEs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
