<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Export Affected by Volatile Currency Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Variations in currency
exchange rates affected India's export growth in 1996-97, the
Reserve Bank of India (RBI) said today.
</P>
<P>
Shifts in the pattern of consumer preference and spending in
major export destinations like the United States, Japan and
countries of the European Union also inflicted a major blow to
Indian exports during 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
Demand for major items of export basket such as clothing,
footwear and leather accessories slackened in these developed
nations and contributed largely to the decline in the overall
exports from India, the RBI said in its annual report for 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
Adding to the problems were the imposition of anti-dumping
duties on imports of textiles by the European Union and the
maintenance of import licensing requirements for a variety of food
and agricultural products in countries like Canada, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Issues relating to environment and child-labor raised during
the year under review also adversely affected the export of items
such as leather products and carpets, the report further said.
</P>
</TEXT>
