<HEADLINE> Yeltsin's Speech at Russian Federation Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Russia has already crossed the
"main line," with a free economy taking its root and a reversion
to the past impossible, said Russian President Boris Yeltsin here
today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Russian Federation Council, Yeltsin said
Russia's industrial downturn has stopped and production increase
has continued this year, reported the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Russia's recent accession to the Paris Club, he noted, "will
help expedite the payment of foreign debts, which run at 140,000
million US dollars."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin added that a reform in the housing-and-utilities system
and other social welfare sector is under way. The State will play
a greater role in the matter but not reverse to the Soviet-style
planning by establishing common rules for businessmen and not
interfering in their legitimate activities.
</P>
<P>
Debts concerning pensions and money allowances to the
servicemen and law enforcement personnel have been repaid, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Yeltsin acknowledged that there are problems still to
be resolved not only in the economy, but also in law-making
practices.
</P>
<P>
He proposed to lift the numerous taxes on agricultural
producers except on land, and to sell more land to private
citizens.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to speed up the anti-corruption drive and to
block the "insolent creeping" of crimes into politics, Yeltsin
warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
