<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Turnaround in Thai Baht Expected Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- International bankers here
are generally of the view that the Thai currency Baht is likely to
continue its downward trend in the coming months before picking up
gradually next year.
</P>
<P>
The Baht dipped to its new lows against the U.S. dollar this
week, reflecting that it takes time to restore market confidence,
according to participants at the ongoing annual meetings of the
World Bank and International Monetary Fund (IMF) here.
</P>
<P>
Although the international community and the Thai government
have reacted to rescue the currency, months of assaults on it have
led to damages to market confidence, bankers said.
</P>
<P>
While excessive speculative trading has been blamed for the
weakening of the Baht, cumulative problems in the Thai economy and
banking sector have stood behind the turmoil, Michael Mussa, IMF
Research Director, said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's economic situation has been deteriorating in recent
years and become increasingly vulnerable since 1993, Mussa said.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that the current account deficit peaked at eight
percent of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) last year as a result of a
sharp slowdown in exports. The situation was also accompanied by a
high external debt equaling to 50 percent of GDP, of which about
40 percent was short-term.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, capital inflows have concentrated on property
development instead of a reasonable distribution in industrial
structure, making economic bubbles swelling.
</P>
<P>
As banks lent heavily to real estate industry, non-performing
loans expanded and banking risks grew, giving rise to inability
of the banking sector to deal with possible crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Baht crisis, which also dragged down currencies of
other Southeast Asian countries, has aroused serious attention of
the international community. A rescue package of 16 billion U.S.
dollar emergency funds has been in place to help Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has designed a medium-term policy framework
to restore market confidence and economic stability, consisting of
a wide range of measures including structural readjustment, export
promotion, public expenditure cut, tax increase and reform of the
banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Under the framework, the current account deficit is expected to
fall to five percent of the GDP this year and three percent of
the GDP next year, while economic growth will keep at 2.5 percent
this year and 3.5 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has strongly committed itself to the
adjustment program, with endorsement and support from the
international community, and implementation of the program is now
under way, Joseph Stiglitz, chief economist of the World Bank,
said.
</P>
<P>
"There should be confidence that the Thai economy will
eventually return to a sound track," he said.
</P>
<P>
But international bankers also noted that the devaluation of
Baht is a market correction to its previous over-valued status
and the market will not move to chase it until recognizing an
improvement in Thai economic situation.
</P>
<P>
"What's important for the market now is when the efforts will
produce substantial results," said Quentin Hills, Citibank's
regional head for Asian capital market business. "If positive
signs can be spotted by the year's end, a turnaround in market
confidence will most probably occur sometime next year."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
