<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Defense Minister Ends Visit to Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 24 (Xinhua) -- British Defense Minister
George Robertson ended his three-day official visit here today
after concluding a Sea Skua missile deal with the Kuwaitis.
</P>
<P>
Robertson announced the sale to Kuwait of British Sea Skua
anti-ship missile systems on Tuesday, saying the contract was
signed between the British Defense Ministry and the Kuwaiti
government.
</P>
<P>
He did not disclose the value of the contract, but independent
sources said the contract is worth about 150 million U.S. dollars
in two stages.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Britain will supply the missiles worth 72
million dollars and the Skua launchers and installation worth
about 78 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Robertson also held lengthy discussions with Kuwaiti
officials on several potential defense deals for British
contractors, diplomatic sources said.
</P>
<P>
Among the outstanding contracts are a contract to provide AS90
self-propelled artillery mobile guns and a contract to upgrade
some 12 Hawk jets Kuwait bought in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Robertson tried to convince the Kuwaiti leaders of the quality
of the mobile guns which he said were deployed in Bosnia and
described "deterrent and effective."
</P>
<P>
The British minister arrived in Kuwait Monday for the first
visit to the region by a British Cabinet minister since the Labor
Party won power in last May.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Kuwait, Robertson also held talks with
Kuwaiti Amir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah, his Kuwaiti
counterpart Sheikh Salem Sabah Al-Salem Al-Sabah and other senior
Kuwaiti officials on ways to boost bilateral military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have reiterated their determination to
strengthen defense cooperation in all fields. They signed a
defense cooperation agreement in 1992 following the 1991 Gulf
War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
