<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SE Asian Nations Urge IMF to Help Prevent Future Crises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asian countries
today urged the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to take measures
 in preventing future currency crises.
</P>
<P>
"The Fund could devise a framework to enable countries to adapt
and cope more effectively with market excesses associated with
destabilizing capital flows," said Anwar Ibrahim, Malaysia's
Deputy Prime Minister.
</P>
<P>
"International rules" should apply not only to IMF members, but
also to "capital market participants", including rules and
principles on "ethical and professional standards," Anwar, who is
also Malaysian Minister of Finance, said at the annual meetings
of the World Bank and the IMF at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
"The contagion effect of the financial crisis which began in
Thailand but spilled over to its neighbors, have reached an
intensity beyond our expectations," Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asian economies have been affected by a currency
crisis sparked by Thailand's devaluation of the Baht on July 2 due
to a huge current account deficit and the disclosure of massive
bad debts in the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that the recent depreciation of the region's
currencies illustrated that sound policies are no guarantee
against speculative activities and highlighted the problems faced
by countries with less sophisticated financial systems.
</P>
<P>
But it had provided the impetus to form a forum to discuss
regional issues as well as explore remedial policy action.
</P>
<P>
This forum now provides a basis for the establishment of a
facility to enhance the IMF's efforts towards economic and
financial stability to support macroeconomic adjustments, Anwar
said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF must be prepared to view the predicament of emerging
economies and the effort to deal with the effect on their markets
caused by speculators, he added.
</P>
<P>
Also at the annual meetings, the Philippines urged the IMF to
take a "more aggressive role" in helping member countries regulate
the financial sector to prevent future currency crises.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo said "volatile capital
inflows will continue to be a challenge" in the years to come,
stressing the answers are not in a return to controls but in
managing these flows better.
</P>
<P>
There must be room for the multilateral institutions to play a
more aggressive role in preventing such crises, he told the WB/IMF
annual meetings.
</P>
<P>
The IMF needs to reinvigorate its surveillance functions and
improve its data dissemination, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting today, Indonesia also expressed its concerns
with the excessive volatility of many currencies which undoubtedly
creates uncertainties in the business community, and in turn could
lead to an economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, I would urge the IMF to take an active role
according to its mandate," said Mar'ie Muhammad, Indonesia's
Finance Minister.
</P>
<P>
Since excessive volatility of currencies can hinder the world
economy, "we warmly welcome any regional or global initiatives to
stabilize currencies," he added.
</P>
<P>
Currency turmoil in Southeast Asia has enhanced Vietnam's
awareness of the need to speed up reform, State Bank of Vietnam's
Deputy Governor Le Duc Thuy said.
</P>
<P>
"Recent developments in the region help to enhance Vietnam's
awareness of the importance of accelerating the reform process,
thus improving efficiency in the use of resources, raising
domestic savings and investment rates, and reducing vulnerability
to external shock," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
