<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transparency Critical to Avoiding Financial Crisis: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- What Mexico learned from
the financial crisis in 1995 is that there should be "much more
transparency in terms of information flow", Mexican Secretary of
Finance and Public Credit Grillermo Ortiz said here today.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the lessons generated from the crisis, he said,
Mexico is now publishing figures of current balance and reserves
regularly. In addition, conferences are held to brief investors
and analysts on the latest developments of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference here today that, from Mexico's
experience, when a crisis breaks out, the first thing to be done
is to diagnose the situation and try to assess the extent of the
damage.
</P>
<P>
At the outset of the crisis, he said, the government should
tell its people that the situation is a delicate one and that
strong measures are needed to redress this situation, because
"otherwise it will be very difficult to explain the harshness."
</P>
<P>
"In our experience, it's much better to confront directly the
problem," said the Mexican Official, who is here attending the
Annual Meetings of the World Bank and International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question on what Latin America can learn from
the Asian experience, he listed long-term high growth and strong
domestic savings, among others, which contribute to the strength
of Asian economies, as things to be learned.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the current financial crisis in Thailand, he said
that with the assistance of the World Bank and the IMF and other
economies in East Asia, "I think the Thai crisis will be easing
off soon."
</P>
<P>
Talking about the Mexican economy, he said, growth in 1997 is
projected to be 6 percent, or perhaps higher.
</P>
<P>
The recovery is based basically on investment, which increased
over 21 percent in the first six months of this year, pointing to
a consolidated growth through 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mexico expects 15 to 16 billion U.S. dollars in capital inflows
for 1997, of which 75 percent is foreign direct investment, he
added.
</P>
<P>
And not only Mexico, but also the whole Latin American region,
will brace a consolidated process of sustained growth forward, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
