</P>
<P>
-- Ulster Unionist Party leaders made history by sitting
at the same conference table as Sinn Fein for the first time
Tuesday, but they emphatically rejected what Sinn Fein
leader Gerry Adams called his "hand of friendship".
</P>
<P>
The Financial Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The British Labor government was facing its first
serious diplomatic crisis Tuesday after a Saudi court
sentenced a British nurse accused of murdering an
Australian colleague to eight years in prison and 500
lashes. The murder victim's lawyers claimed a second nurse
had been sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
The Independent:
</P>
<P>
-- Senior industrialists will today tell Prime Minister
Tony Blair that business is being hurt by the strength of
sterling and the lack of commitment to entering a single
currency when they attend a working breakfast in Downing
Street. In return, the Prime Minister will tell his guests
that he wants to see more job swaps between business and
Whitehall.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph:
</P>
<P>
-- Britain's Liberal Democrats Leader Paddy Ashdown will
deliver a blunt warning to his colleagues that they must be
prepared to "take risks" in co-operating with Labor if they
are to achieve their long-cherished ambition of proportional
representation.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian:
</P>
<P>
-- Britain is at the start of a social revolution as it
leads the world into becoming a "24-hour society" where
people work, shop and play at all times of the day and
night. 
</P>
