<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Northern Ireland's Protestant Unionists and Sinn Fein
republicans sat face to face at the negotiating table Tuesday for
the first time since the partitioning of Ireland in 1921. But the
Ulster Unionist Party used the encounter to demand the expulsion of
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA. But their chances of being
listened to by Prime Minister Tony Blair are zero, as the British
government intends to win a negotiated solution with Sinn Fein which
represents 41 percent of the votes of the Catholic community in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- A study by the state statistics and economic institute INSEE
said that inheritance remains the most sure way to become rich in
France today, and the chances for a well-paid and hard-working
salary-owner to make a fortune are almost zero. There are 200
million households regarded as ``rich'' with about 10 million francs
(1.7 million US dollars) of heritage.
</P>
<P>
-- With its finger burnt by terrorist attacks in France launched
by Islamic extremists of Algeria, the French government maintains
the minimalist policy made by former Prime Minister Alain Juppe
toward Algeria, which limits its reaction toward violence in Algeria
to expressing regret. 
</P>
</TEXT>
