<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algeria's Islamic Salvation Army Declares Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Islamic Salvation Army (AIS),
the armed wing of the outlawed Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) of Algeria,
today announced a ceasefire with the government from October 1,
according to a communique by the armed group.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, which was signed by AIS National Emir Madani
Mezerag on September 21 and faxed to Agence France-Presse (AFP)
Bonn bureau today, AIS called on other armed Islamic groups in
Algeria "attached to Islam and the nation" to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
But it finger-pointed the Armed Islamic Group (GIA), which is
believed to be the most radical and bloody armed group in Algeria,
as "a criminal group".
</P>
<P>
This communique was apparently prepared before the latest
massacre took place in Bentalha south of Algiers, in which around
200 civilians, most of them women and children, were killed from
Monday night to Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
AIS said that to "arrive at a just and legitimate solution,
the National Emir of the Islamic Salvation Army orders all the
chiefs of the combatting companies under its command to stop
combat operations from... October 1, 1997."
</P>
<P>
AIS "calls on all other groups attached to the interests of
the religion and the nation to respond to this appeal in order to
expose the enemy who hides behind the abominable massacres and to
isolate the criminals of the GIA (Armed Islamic Group) and those
who hide behind them," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
The communique was issued several weeks after Abassi Madani, the
former FIS chief who was released from jail three months ago, said
he would appeal for a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
AIS said that "after contacts which have been going on for
a long time" with unspecified Algerian institutions, it decided
to "put the enemies of yesterday and today before their
responsibilities" to "encourage the sons of Algeria to take
initiative to act together for the return of security and
stability to let the country go out of the crisis."
</P>
<P>
It said that the release of Madani had "pushed the enemies of
yesterday and today to manipulate the pawns in the game to fan the
flame of fire of disorder and foil all susceptible project to
animate the country and motivate the citizens."
</P>
<P>
It described the massacres of civilians as "abominable carnages
rarely seen in the modern history of humanity" which remind one of
the "dreadful scenes lived by our people on the eve of
independence" from France in 1962.
</P>
<P>
It calls on Algerians to "unite their efforts" as the
"situation is dangerous and the conspiracy is great". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
