<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Ranks Fourth in HIV/AIDS in Africa: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is the fourth highest
country hardest hit with HIV/AIDS in Africa, with 25 percent of
the population being HIV/AIDS positive.
</P>
<P>
Opening the seventh national AIDS conference here Tuesday,
Vice-president Brigadier-general Miyanda said one in every four
adults in Zambia is infected with the disease, making the country
rank 4th in HIV/AIDS infection following Kenya, Uganda and South
Africa, according to "The Post" paper today.
</P>
<P>
"Zambia is at the butt of Africa's AIDS bed which stretches
from Kenya through Uganda down to South Africa," Miyanda was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He told the conference whose theme is collaboration in the
fight against HIV/AIDS that infection is prevalent between the
ages of 20-30 in females and 30-40 in males.
</P>
<P>
Miyanda disclosed the number of orphaned children as a result
of the HIV/AIDS pandemic has increased and is now between
300,000-500,000.
</P>
<P>
During 1995 alone, between 600,000 to 700,000 Zambians were
estimated to be HIV/AIDS positive and between 40,000 to 50,000
people were said to have died of the disease, according to an
earlier report by a state-owned newspaper Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Statistics based on computer projections for HIV/AIDS released
last week show that the rates of infection in Zambia will peak at
about 27 percent of the adult population by 1998 and the rates
will continue to rise rapidly toward the end of this decade and
possibly into the next.
</P>
<P>
In referring to some claims that safe sex methods have been
introduced in the Zambian market, Miyanda stressed that there is
need to stop casual sex instead of encouraging it because the
country is at the center of the AIDS belt.
</P>
<P>
"Don't go out to experiment with methods of prevention which
are not fool proof," Miyanda added.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president challenged the participants including
delegates from Zimbabwe and South Africa to come up with serious
conclusions that will help check the problem of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the Zambian government is ready to work with
non-governmental organizations in the fight against AIDS and is
in the process of formulating an AIDS council whose secretariat
would be based at his office.
</P>
<P>
At the three-day meeting, Elizabeth Mataka, Zambia National
AIDS Network chairperson, blamed the rapid spread of AIDS on the
incidence of sexual abuse of children and called on the
government to stiffen the law against child abuse.
</P>
<P>
She said the child abuse is not only "traumatic" to the
victims but posed a real danger in the spread of HIV/AIDS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taylor No More Wanted in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles
Taylor can now visit the U. S. without fear of being arrested,
following the dismissal by an American district magistrate's
court of the extradition charges filed against him 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
A press report said today that Liberia earlier this month sent
a note to the U.S. authorities, saying that it had "withdrawn its
request for the extradition of Mr. Taylor".
</P>
<P>
Once a senior official with President Samuel Doe's government,
Taylor was charged with corruption and escaped to the U.S. in
1984.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested in Boston in May of the same year, but later
mysteriously broke the jail before he was extradited to Monrovia
as requested by the then Liberian government.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after he was elected the president last month, reports
quoted a U.S. court as saying that Taylor will be arrested if he
dares into U.S., because the extradition charge is still there.
</P>
</TEXT>
