<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAPEC: World Oil Demand to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The world demand on oil
during the last quarter of 1997 will increase 2.4 million barrels
per day (bpd) over the same period of last year, according to a
monthly bulletin of an international oil exports organization.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait-based Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting
Countries said in its September bulletin, which is available here
today, that the world demand on oil in the last quarter of 1997
will reach 75.9 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
The global demand of crude in 1997 may surge to an average of
73.5 million bpd compared to last year's 71.8 million bpd and 69.9
million bpd in 1995.
</P>
<P>
It projected that the world supply of oil and liquefied
petroleum gas (LPG) will reach 46.8 million bpd during the last
quarter of 1997, excluding that of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's oil and LPG supply will be slightly over 29.1 million
bpd during the final quarter of this year, compared to 28.8
million bpd in the same period of 1996, the bulletin
estimated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
