<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Official on Capital Account Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The process of the capital
account liberalization must be paced in accordance with the actual
circumstances of each country, a senior official of the
International Monetary Fund IMF) said here today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Chinese reporters covering the World
Bank/IMF annual meetings being held in Hong Kong, Manuel Guitian,
director of the Monetary and Exchange Affairs Department of the
IMF, said that the IMF believes that the liberalization of capital
flows is important because it can increase the efficiency in the
use of savings and the welfare of all member countries.
</P>
<P>
"However, we are also aware that a very open and very
liberalized system of capital movement can cause problems for
these countries," Guitain added.
</P>
<P>
The interest of the IMF in free capital movement is not
associated just in liberalization itself, but in its being
implemented and sustained, Guitian stressed.
</P>
<P>
So, it is not enough to achieve a liberalization of capital, he
said, adding that it has to be achieved in a way that it can be
sustained.
</P>
<P>
This is a very important subject because in today's very
integrated international economy, no country can afford to isolate
itself and exist.
</P>
<P>
The challenge is that there is no way to benefit from the
opportunities that the capital flows provide without being exposed
to the risks.
</P>
<P>
The process of China's capital account liberalization will have
to be paced to the speed with which the domestic reforms can be
undertaken, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Backs Military Justice System in Ethiopia: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to
Ethiopia David Shinn said Washington is ready to continue its
relationship with Ethiopia in the area of military justice
training program.
</P>
<P>
According to today's ''Ethiopian Herald'', speaking at a brief
graduation ceremony held at the defense forces officers' club
here Tuesday, the U.S. ambassador said the purpose of the joint
United States and Ethiopia military justice program was to assist
Ethiopian military personnel in the important work of creating a
military justice system for the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the program focused on the legal basis for United
Nations peace-keeping operations and examined the many and
diverse legal challenges encountered in carrying out such
operation.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, 32 members of the Ethiopian
National Defense Forces participated in a week-long military
justice and peace-keeping operations training program conducted by a
team of four military attorney from the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
