<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Farmers Pin Hopes of Prosperity on Having Sons (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Village officials in charge of
family planning in the Dabie Mountain area, one of the poorest
regions in central China, are now welcomed into the homes of the
farmers who for years turned away authorities urging them not to
have more children.
</P>
<P>
Until a few years ago, China's family planning workers spent
most of their time persuading poor farmers to abide by the
country's one-child policy, which many of the farmers believe
violates the old Chinese belief that sons are a sign of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Now, family planners work to help poor farmers out of poverty
by offering incentives to stick to the one-child policy.
</P>
<P>
In Chinese cities, a couple is allowed to have only one child;
in rural areas, if a farmer's first child is a girl, the parents
may have a second child.
</P>
<P>
Poverty-stricken mountainous areas have the biggest problems
with family planning, according to officials. The birth rate in
these areas is higher than the country's average.
</P>
<P>
Dabie Mountain is located at an area where Anhui, Hubei and
Henan provinces meet.
</P>
<P>
Li Xianguo, a farmer with two daughters in Madian Village,
Jinzhai County of Anhui Province, said that three years ago
family planners in the village asked him not to have a third
child. Li said he became so fixated on the idea of having a son
that he was unable to do his job. His family lived in a straw hut,
and he earned less than 300 yuan (36 dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Bao, a county magistrate, learned of Li's situation during
an inspection tour of the village. Determined to help Li's family,
Zhao bought more than 100 kilograms of tea seeds and over 100
Chinese chestnut saplings for the poor farmer.
</P>
<P>
Li has so far planted 0.13 hectares of tea and 0.23 hectares of
Chinese chestnuts. He expects to earn 1,100 yuan (about 140
dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
The 34-year-old father has already given up the idea of having
a son, and is applying to contract more uncultivated mountain land
to grow Chinese chestnuts and traditional Chinese medicine.
</P>
<P>
Li is among 10 million farmers in the Dabie Mountain area who
have changed their thinking about having big families.
</P>
<P>
Yu Yunxiu, deputy director of Jinzhai County's family planning
commission, said that convincing the farmers to follow the
one-child policy takes a lot of time and effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Farmers Pin Hopes of Prosperity on Having Sons (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But the job has become simpler, as the primary task for family
planners now is to seek loans and arrange relief projects for
farmers, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Hong, a farmer with two girls, had a vasectomy at the
urging of local family planning workers. When he needed funds to
run a furniture factory, the village officials offered him 3,000
yuan (360 dollars).
</P>
<P>
His factory earned 200,000 yuan (26,800 dollars) in profits
last year, and Jiang said he would not have been able to borrow
the necessary funds if his did not become a model family-planning
household.
</P>
<P>
In a sign of support for family planning, all 23 workers at
Jiang's factory are from poor households that strictly observe the
family-planning regulations. The workers' annual income has
reached 6,000 yuan, three times higher than the country's average
in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Jinzhai County annually allocates more than five million yuan
in special funds to support poor farmers who observe the
family-planning policy. Each of the households which abide by the
policy can receive an average of 1,000 yuan (120 dollars) in
poverty relief and 400 yuan (48 dollars) in pension insurance.
</P>
<P>
So far, the county has built 82 old folks homes and bought
pension insurance for 12,000 parents who abide by the family
planning regulations.
</P>
<P>
Zhao, the magistrate, said that apart from offering funds for
aid-the-poor projects, the county government has also stipulated
that school children from one-child or two-daughter families can
remit their tuition or enjoy free education, and will be given
priority consideration for receiving Hope Project donations.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said the yearly income of families in his county who abide
by the state family planning policy will exceed 2,500 yuan (304
dollars) by 2000. The country's average income level in rural area
last year was 1,900 yuan.
</P>
<P>
In the past 20 years, the Dabie Mountain area has given six
million less births.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the State Family Planning Commission showed
that from 1979 to 1996, the birth rate in China had dropped nearly
50 percent, or giving about 300 million people less births.
</P>
</TEXT>
