<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Painters Should Drink Deep of Native Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Ding Shaoguang, a famous
Chinese painter living in the United States, has called on fellow
painters to take a deep drink of Chinese culture to gain higher
status in the international painting arena.
</P>
<P>
During a recent symposium held in this capital of north China's
Shanxi Province, Ding said his 18-year stay in the US renewed his
interest in the traditional culture of his motherland, and that
for most Chinese painters who live in the US or Europe, the
Chinese culture has become the heart of their artistic creation.
</P>
<P>
His achievement as a painter abroad is greatly due to the
influence of ancient Chinese painters, even the patterns on the
crudest ancient painted pottery and paper-cut works, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Only after fully understanding Western art and comparing it
with the Chinese culture have I realized the long-lasting appeal
of my mother culture," Ding remarked.
</P>
<P>
He told participants that more and more Western painters are
turning to oriental cultures, especially the traditional Chinese
culture, for new inspiration. The combination of ancient and
modern, abstract and concrete, Eastern and Western art forms is
becoming the dominant trend on the world painting arena, he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Born in Yuncheng in Shanxi Province, Ding studied painting at
the Central Institute of Arts and Crafts in Beijing. On three
occasions, his works were selected by the United Nations as
designs for commemorative stamps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
