<HEADLINE> Tourism Creates Thousands of Jobs in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of new tourism jobs
will be created as Zimbabwe Sun Company builds new hotels and
runs joint venture of safari camps with local businessmen, local
daily "The Herald" reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the company will build six new hotels
and three giant resort complexes at Victoria Falls, Kariba and
Nyanga, and run joint-venture safari camps with indigenous
businessmen in a 1.2 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (100 million U.S.
Dollars) investment.
</P>
<P>
Briefing journalists on the group's future plans, Zimbabwe Sun
Chief Executive John Smith said yesterday the group's hotel,
safari and resort divisions will undergo extensive changes in the
next millennium.
</P>
<P>
The company is trying to ensure that indigenous business
people enter tourism at a high level, he said, adding that his
company plans to invite indigenous partners at both operational
and ownership levels in the safari division.
</P>
<P>
Smith said, "we are sympathetic to the government's calls for
indigenization. The arrangements are on equal partnership basis.
Zimbabwe Sun provides project financing and start-up capital and
also assists with expertise in human resources development and
marketing."
</P>
<P>
Tourism is already one of Zimbabwe's largest industries and a
major employer. Being a labor-intensive industry, tourism's rapid
expansion creates jobs as well as markets for many local
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Already around one million people visit Zimbabwe each year,
the report revealed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
