<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Artificial Rainfall Helps Relieve Drought in Northwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Cloud-seeding and other
techniques for making artificial rain have helped to relieve
drought in this arid land of northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Since early this year, Gansu Province has sent 28 planes,
flying a total of more than 30,000 kilometers, to produce 700
million cubic meters of artificial rainfall through a process
known as cloud-seeding, in which chemicals are released into the
clouds to produce rain.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another technique which uses artillery shells to
melt hailstones in the sky, has been used more than 1,000 times,
to prevent crop damage from hail and increase the amount of rain.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Gansu was hit by a serious drought which covered a
large part of the province and lasted for months. The local
government sent 43 planes for cloud-seeding in the spring, summer
and autumn, and created 890 million cubic meters of rain.
</P>
<P>
In Yongchang County, where the drought had lingered for 75
days, the water supply in the country reservoir in 1995 was
increased by 12 million cubic meters through artificial
rainfall. The country's grain output rose by eight million kg in
the year.
</P>
<P>
Located in northwest China, Gansu is often plagued by drought
and hailstorms, said Xie Jinnan, director of the province's
meteorological bureau.
</P>
<P>
In the past six years, 51 of the province's 86 counties have
been benefited from the artificial rainfall, which guaranteed the
good harvests in these years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
