<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Press Condemns Massacre of Civilians in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- French press today condemned
the massacre of more than 200 civilians in Bentalha south of
Algiers Monday night, and many papers carried on the front page
the picture of women grieving after their family members were
killed.
</P>
<P>
The daily Liberation said that the international community should
send neutral investigators to Algeria to see what is really going on
there, while the daily Ouest-France said that one ``becomes
criminal'' if he closes his eyes before the atrocities in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The daily La Provence said that when violence in Algeria enters
this stage, one can no longer say they are killings but should call
them genocide.
</P>
<P>
The daily La Depeche du Midi criticized the international
community for maintaining ``a silence of death'' over Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The daily L'Yonne Republicaine said that the war in Algeria has
turned into a fratricide carried on by the military-industrial
ruling complex of Algeria which refuses to yield anything.
</P>
<P>
According to latest reports by Algerian newspaper El Watan, the
number of people killed in Bentalha was from 200 to 250, while the
Algerian daily Tribune quoted hospital sources as saying that 178
people were killed.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian government said 85 people were killed in the
massacre and ``categorically'' denied the figures reported by
foreign press, which put it at around 200.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 100,000 people have been killed in Algeria since
1992, when the country was plunged into violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
