<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF's Debt Relief Plan Beyond Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenya will not benefit from
a joint World Bank-International Monetary Fund (IMF) initiative
to help heavily-indebted developing countries because it is able
to service its foreign debts, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's external debt up to December 1996 was estimated to
total 6.2 billion U.S. Dollars, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
IMF resident representative in Nairobi Raimer Carstens was
quoted as saying that the initiative to assist heavily-indebted
poor states would be discussed during the IMF-World Bank annual
meeting in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Kenya is not on the preliminary list of this initiative
because its external indebtedness is not that bad. The country is
still in a position to service its debts, which may increase the
confidence of investors and donors," said Carstens.
</P>
<P>
The initiative, endorsed by the two institutions last year, is
intended to reward countries which have a good record in economic
reforms by offering them easy debt relief.
</P>
<P>
He said that only Burkina Faso, Cote d'Ivoire and Uganda has
been considered in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Bolivia is the only non-African country to benefit from the
initiative, Carstens added.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Moi complained last week that donors were
imposing extremely harsh conditions before giving aid to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The IMF suspended a 205-million-Dollar aid package to Kenya in
July after accusing Nairobi of not doing enough to combat high
level corruption.
</P>
<P>
However, "the IMF hopes that this recent show of commitment by
the Kenyan government will pave the way for the second enhanced
structural adjustment facility to proceed without a hitch and
that Kenyan's economic growth will pick up after the elections,"
Carstens said.
</P>
<P>
"The IMF is only reiterating the conditions of restructuring
economy" of this east African country, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
