<HEADLINE> Wu Yi Stresses Trade Relations with Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Wu Yi, Chinese minister of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation today reaffirmed China's
emphasis on economic and trade cooperation with Cambodia and noted
the favorable conditions and great potential for further
development.
</P>
<P>
Wu pointed to the fact that China and Cambodia forged
diplomatic ties over 40 years ago and have since closely
coordinated economic and trade activities.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the remarks during talks with Sok An, visiting
Cambodian minister in charge of the Cabinet of Ministers.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that China is satisfied with the quick recovery of
bilateral trade and economic relations, especially since the
proclamation of the government of the Kingdom of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for the first half of this year show a bilateral
trade volume of 62.7 million US dollars, a dramatic 91 percent
rise on the corresponding period in 1996. Statistics also show a
record trade volume of 70.3 million US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
China and Cambodia are currently facing similar tasks related
to economic development, and upgrading the living standards of
their people, said Wu, adding the Chinese government is ready to
push bilateral economic and trade ties up to a new plateau based
on the principle of equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
China hopes to expand personnel exchanges between business
sectors in the two nations, and encourages strong Chinese
enterprises to either invest or establish joint ventures in
Cambodia, said Wu.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 Chinese enterprises have established resident agencies
in Cambodia, while others have earmarked a total of 70 million US
dollars for investments in the country.
</P>
<P>
Sok An said it is a necessity for both countries to tighten
economic and trade relations to ensure mutual economic
development, protect the interests of their people, and to promote
the potential of the region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Chinese enterprises are welcome to invest in Cambodia in
sectors such as petroleum, natural gas, and hydropower, as well as
export-oriented processing and industrial bases, said Sok. He also
pointed out that Cambodia has adopted preferential policies to
encourage related cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
