<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Languages Face Crisis in Future: Lecturer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean scientist has
warned that African languages face extinction unless governments
stop sidelining them in favor of foreign ones.
</P>
<P>
Lecturer of National University of Science and Technology Temba
Dlodlo predicted Tuesday that if nothing was done about the use of mother
tongues as official languages, then 100 years from today, the only
thing to remain African about the people of the continent would be
their blackness.
</P>
<P>
''Our language and cultures will be extinct, while our situation
will be like that of black Americans who now call themselves
Afro-Americans although their only link with the continent is the
color of their skin,'' Dlodlo said in a presentation to the
Scholarstica 97 Conference which started Tuesday in the country's
second largest city of Bulawayo.
</P>
<P>
He said while blackness might be considered a necessary
characteristic requirement for being African, it was not sufficient
as it had to come with the embracing of the languages and cultures of
the indigenous Africans that constitute the Africaness.
</P>
<P>
He said the use of mother tongue as language of instruction in
Africa would result in more pupils taking up science and technology
courses at colleges and universities, particularly those from rural
communities where the command of English language was inadequate.
</P>
<P>
''More African scientists would be produced which will result in
their making contributions in research, which will bring about the
spread of science and technology on the continent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
This would also create, Dlodlo said, a high degree of self-worth
and self-respect which were currently lacking because of the feeling
of inadequacy that most people have when they cannot communicate in
English in the right accent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
