<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suzhou and Riga Become Sister Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Suzhou, a popular tourist city
in east China's Jiangsu Province, and Riga, capital of the
Republic of Latvia, recently signed an agreement on the
establishment of a sister city relationship.
</P>
<P>
Riga, which covers 307 sq.km. and has a population of 840,000,
will be China's first international sister city in the Baltic
States.
</P>
<P>
Riga established exchanges with Suzhou in 1989 as a means of
promoting sister city relations. A city government delegation, led
by Deputy Mayor Juris Ritins, signed the document in Suzhou on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Yang Xiaotang, secretary of the Suzhou City Committee of the
Communist Party of China, met with Ritins, prior to the signing
ceremony. They expressed the hope for improving cultural and
economic communications between the two cities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
