<HEADLINE> Former Tanzanian President Stresses Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's retired
president Julius Nyerere has stressed that concerted efforts
should be taken by the government and Tanzanians in general to
ensure that primary education is available to all children.
</P>
<P>
According to local press today, he made the remarks when
addressing local journalists at his home in Musoma on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said, "primary education is a right of every child. We must
find ways to make it available to them."
</P>
<P>
He urged the establishment of a system to ensure that all
children, including the street ones, are enrolled in primary
schools.
</P>
<P>
The present rate of primary school enrollment in Tanzania
stands at 77 percent. It reached 98 percent in 1981 but
drastically dropped to 65 percent later due to several factors
including the general fall in the standard of education. 
