<HEADLINE> East African Coop in Health Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and
Uganda have been urged to enhance cooperation among them in
health sector, the local newspaper "Daily News" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Countries in the east African region should cooperate in the
prevention and control of communicable diseases, especially
the sexually transmitted ones, like AIDS, Deputy Executive
Secretary of the East African Cooperation (EAC), Fulgence Kazaura
said at an east African health sector conference in Arusha,
northern Tanzania, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that communicable diseases impose the heaviest burden
on health systems in the three east African countries.
</P>
<P>
"The areas of cooperation designated under the health sector
will, therefore, broadly involve cooperation in the control and
prevention of diseases with emphasis on HIV/AIDS," said Kazaura.
</P>
<P>
He also cited other areas of cooperation, such as specialized
training, manpower development, production and procurement of
health learning materials, equipment, pharmaceutical and medical
services.
</P>
<P>
Kazaura stressed, "investment in health services is investment
in a more productive population."
</P>
<P>
It is the first meeting of the health sector under the
auspices of the EAC and is expected to identify health programs
that have regional character and discuss networking system for
strengthening existing health capacity services. 
</P>
