<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guidelines Need Parliamentary Approval, Opposition Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Japanese opposition parties
today demanded that the government should gain parliamentary
approval for the just finalized review of the 1978 Guidelines for
Japan-U.S. Defense Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The opposition New Frontier Party (NFP),the Democratic Party of
Japan (DPJ) and the Japanese Communist Party (JCP) said the new
guidelines need parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
Some of the proposed Japan-U.S. joint actions under the new
guidelines would go against the Japanese Constitution, the NFP
said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the JCP Criticized the new guidelines as
creating a mechanism under which Japan will automatically be
involved in war when the United States starts military
intervention in the Asia-Pacific region under the pretext of
dealing with an emergency in areas surrounding Japan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Asahi Shimbun, a leading Japanese newspaper,
called for steps to prevent the new guidelines from becoming a
system that automatically drags Japan into U.S.-led wars.
</P>
<P>
"Real civilian control under politics based on sound security
views" will be required to prevent such a scenario, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The paper also said Japan's support for the U.S. military in
areas surrounding Japan as proposed in the new guidelines could
violate Japan's Constitution, which bans the exercise of the right
to collective self-defense and the use abroad of military force.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of (Japanese)politicians have not freed themselves from
the Cold War-era idea that Japan's security and interests can be
maintained only if Japan follows U.S. leadership in the
(bilateral military) alliance," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the United States adopted the new guidelines in New
York on Tuesday, drastically expanding the scope of Japan's
support for U.S. forces in the event of emergencies around Japan.
</P>
<P>
The new guidelines stipulate 40 items pertaining to
Japan-U.S. cooperation in the event of emergencies surrounding
Japan. Some of the items lack a clear legal basis in Japan,
defense experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
