<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Surgery for Unclogging Arteries Successful in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Doctors at the No. 1 Hospital
of the Harbin Medical University have cured a patient with clogged
arteries to the heart through a series of angioplasty operations.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time the new technique was used in China.
</P>
<P>
Jin Songlin, a worker from Wandashan Pharmaceutical Plant in
Mishan City, northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, experienced
numbness in his legs and had difficulty in walking about three months
ago.
</P>
<P>
When Jin was admitted to the hospital, renowned cardiologist
Dr. Meng Fanchao found that more than 90 percent of Jin's
abdominal aorta was blocked, and only a tiny stream of blood was
flowing to his lower limbs.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Meng decided to try angioplasty, in which a small balloon
is passed through the patient's arteries to dilate them. As the
operation progressed, Jin felt the warmth return to his legs and
his pain was diminished.
</P>
<P>
Several days later, he was up and walking and was soon
discharged.
</P>
<P>
Chinese doctors usually treat clogged arteries by artificial
bypass, which can easily cause coronary thrombosis. This
technique puts patients at high risk, due to the repeated opening
of the abdominal cavity to stop the thrombosis.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that the new technique may become more
popular in treating the artery ailment than the former. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Effectively Protects Wetlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Local sources report that
effective protection has been introduced to the Beihai Wetlands,
Tengchong County, the only natural reserve of its kind in
southwest China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
Wetlands, which are natural ecosystems with various species of
flora and fauna, are noted for their great capacity to purge
sewage and conserve water, according to experts. Wetlands are thus
ideal natural reserves and habitats for many rare species of wild
plants and waterfowl.
</P>
<P>
The Beihai Wetlands Reserve covers about 2,000 hectares and is
divided into two major sections -- Beihai Marshland and Qinghai
Lake, a freshwater lake used for irrigation.
</P>
<P>
The reserve is home to a wide variety of precious plants and
bird species, and is the winter home for well over 1,000 migratory
birds.
</P>
<P>
The Beihai Wetlands were placed under state protection in 1992,
and Tengchong County has established a special agency and issued
wide-ranging regulations to protect the area.
</P>
<P>
Planned afforestation has been carried out in the reserve and
surrounding areas in recent years, with strict regulations in
place to prohibit poaching. The local governments at all levels
have also extended great efforts to teach people to cherish the
natural environment and protect wild animals and plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi's Biggest River Drying Up: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Malawi's biggest river, which
supplies water for the country's hydro-electric power plants and
major industrial city Blantyre, is shrinking and may dry up
entirely as a result of falling water levels in Lake Malawi.
</P>
<P>
Zambia News Agency quoted Richard Watts, Professor of
Hydrology at the University of Malawi, said Tuesday that the
Shire river is already very shallow and the declining water level
of Lake Malawi, can gradually dry the river up.
</P>
<P>
Unless the shallow strip between the Shire river and Lake
Malawi is dredged to increase its depth or large pumps are
installed to pump water into the river, hydro-electric schemes in
southern Malawi will be seriously affected, Watts warned.
</P>
<P>
The Shire river, which originates from Lake Malawi, the third
largest lake in central Africa with an area of 28,678 square
kilometers, runs about 500 kilometers from the north to the
south. On the middle of the river, three hydro-electric power
plants have been set up and they account for 76 percent of hydro
capacity in the country.
</P>
<P>
Blantyre, the country's major industrial city, and sugar
plantations on the lower Shire in southern Malawi, also get their
water supply from the Shire river.
</P>
<P>
Hydrologists say the level of Lake Malawi has been dropping
over the past five years and will drop to about 473 meters above
the sea level by October this year.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that water level of the lake once fell
to 469.9 meters at the beginning of the 20th century, which led
to the complete drying up of the Shire river.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the British Institute of Hydrology who recently
conducted a study on Lake Malawi also warned that problems could
occur if the water level dips too low.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of a return to historically low levels is of
great concern to hydrologists and engineers, particularly in
relation to the maintenance and planning of future hydro-power
developments, the institute said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The serious effect in the future of the Shire river's drying
up has made Malawi's electricity supply authorities map out
contingency plans to avert power cuts.
</P>
<P>
Raynold Duncan, Chief Executive of the Electricity Supply
Commission of Malawi (ESCOM) disclosed that the commission plans
to build a dam to control the flow of water in the Shire river
and studies are underway to explore the use of coal in power
generation.
</P>
<P>
ESCOM is also discussing importing power from Mozambique,
Duncan added. 
</P>
