<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Olympics to Avoid "Commercial Feeding Frenzy" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- International Olympic
Committee marketing chief Michael Payne said in Sydney that he was
confident Sydney would avoid a "commercial feeding frenzy" seen in
Atlanta which was worse than the IOC could have imagined.
</P>
<P>
Payne, the IOC's Worldwide Marketing Director, said the city of
Atlanta had worked "actively against the organizing committee" but
Sydney would be guarded from that because of its partnership
between government and business.
</P>
<P>
Payne, in Sydney to attend a sponsor's workshop for the next
four Olympics, summer and winter, talked of the problems of ambush
marketing, where advertisers try to cash in on the Games without
paying for rights.
</P>
<P>
Payne said:"You're here as the host city, you want to put your
best foot forward to the world, you don't want to confuse the
presentation, and we found that the city turned it into a
commercial feeding frenzy outside of the official sponsors.
</P>
<P>
"That's what the world saw and that was a serious problem which
sadly, a year before the Games, the IOC had already identified.
(But) even in our wildest dreams we didn't think it would be that
bad."
</P>
<P>
He added:"If you want to talk about ambush marketing, the city
ambushed itself -- that was the biggest ambush incident in
Atlanta." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
