<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Needs More Time to Fully Float Rupee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- An earlier three-year
schedule for implementing full convertibility of the rupee is
likely to be stretched to five years in India, a government
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
A delayed time-table is being considered due to growing concern
within the Finance Ministry over sporadic export growth and the
extreme volatility of the rupee.
</P>
<P>
A high-level committee headed by Finance Secretary Montek Singh
Ahluwalia reportedly favors deferring all major measures for
introducing full convertibility till the government is convinced
that the country is on track for sustained and robust export
growth, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Export growth in the country has been sporadic during the first
five years of liberalization, with 1991-93 witnessing average
annual growth of less than five percent. From 1993-94 to 1995-96,
however, exports grew at an annual average of 20 percent. Export
growth again slumped to 1.8 percent in April-July this year, he
further said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Finance Ministry has been concerned about
the rupee's volatility on the foreign exchange front in the
country. The post-budget months saw the appreciation of the rupee
while it has depreciated substantially after August 21. The
government had to move in with policy measures to "soft land" the
rupee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
