<HEADLINE> Food Insecurity to Appear in Nepal: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Nepal will face a situation
of food insecurity within five or six years as the country's
agricultural sector has not been able to keep pace with population
growth, a report warns.
</P>
<P>
Despite Nepal's best efforts, performance in the agricultural
sector has been below the expected level, said the report issued
by the Special Program on Food Production in Support of Food
Security in Nepal (SPIN).
</P>
<P>
And the country's population is expected to reach about 24
million by 2002/2003, while the food production will experience a
deficit of 251,120 metric tons, today's newspapers quoted the
report as saying.
</P>
<P>
"To contain this situation, priority must be on improving the
capacity of the higher potential agricultural land to support the
expanding population of the country," said the report.
</P>
<P>
S.B. Mathema, team leader of the SPIN, said Nepal has the
potential to increase food grain production and the suitable
technologies are available within the country.
</P>
<P>
"Food security is not achieved mainly because of lack of
dissemination of recommended package of technologies in larger
areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali Ministry of Agriculture and the UN Food and
Agriculture Organization jointly launched a pilot project of the
SPIN in October 1995 to boost food production so as to meet
growing demand and help eradicate food insecurity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
