<HEADLINE> Western Countries Urge India to Relax Import Curbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States and
European countries, India's major trading partners, have urged
India to further ease its import curbs, official sources said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The western countries have indicated they would ask for a
dispute settlement panel to be set up if India did not revise its
offer on the removal of import curbs.
</P>
<P>
While India has offered to remove almost 50 percent of the US
priority items during the first phase over a period of three
years, the US has been seeking removal of 1,680 tariff lines which
constitute 61 percent of the priority items.
</P>
<P>
India has proposed to remove its import curbs in six to seven
years. The developed countries are insisting that India must
indicate a year-by-year time schedule which lists out when each
tariff line will be put on the open general license list. India
has so far refused to say when exactly the items will be freed.
</P>
<P>
The trading partners have said that they would ask for the
setting up of a dispute panel on the issue unless India comes
forward with a new revised offer. After the filing of a request
for such a panel, another 30 days are allowed for the country to
appeal against the setting up of the panel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
