<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Settle Debts With Poland, Hungary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria will continue to
settle its debts with Poland and Hungary, said Trade and Tourism
Minister Valentin Vassilev at a news conference today.
</P>
<P>
The debts were incurred before the disbanding of Council for
Mutual Economic Assistance (COMECOM) and calculated in
transferrable rubles -- the currency with which former socialist
countries in Eastern Europe settled payments in the past.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's debts to Hungary currently amounts to 85.9 million
transferable rubles (14,671 U.S. dollars at current exchange
rate). Contracts have been signed for the export of Bulgarian
goods to Hungary worth more than 72 million transferable rubles
(12,297 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's debts to Poland reaches 101 million transferable
rubles (17,297 dollars). The debts are expected to be repaid
through exports of Bulgarian trucks, wine, tractors and machine
tools to Poland.
</P>
<P>
So far, agreements have been concluded by several Bulgarian
companies, including the farm machines manufacturer Agrotechnica,
the Vidimex cosmetics firm, the Prodexim foreign trade company and
the Glavbolgarstroy construction firm, for exports totalling 99.7
million transferable rubles (17,028 dollars). 
</P>
