<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Promises New Boost for Ties With Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Italy is ready to lend new drive
to further political, economic and cultural relations with Latin
American countries, Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of some 20 Latin American ambassadors to
Rome, who gathered for the new quarters of the Italian-Latin
American Institute (ILA), Prodi said his government was aware that
relations with Latin American countries failed to fulfill their
potentialities in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Latin America is now at the center of attention in North
America and Europe and is not from a "colonialist" point of
view. Thus, a new era for these relations can be spoken of, the
premier said.
</P>
<P>
Recalling that Latin American nations have given rise to four
common markets and nine free trade treaties, Prodi said he
believed that the impressive economic development now visible in
Latin America would lead to "prolonged growth over time because it
is based on relations of cooperation among the states and
especially on democracy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
