<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors House Calls,  New Trend in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Responding to an emergency
medical call, doctors and nurses rushed to the home of 90-year-old
Li Boliang, who had slipped into a coma caused by a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to their speedy reaction, the "angels in white" were
able to revive the elderly man.
</P>
<P>
More and more doctors in Shanghai are making house calls, a new
trend which Chinese experts say is the result of the people's
increasing demand for better medical services and their
higher living standards.
</P>
<P>
And a group of medical service stations have opened in the
country's commercial center to deliver medical treatment right to
a patient's doorstep.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals in the Jingan District recently organized a
first-aid team and published their pager numbers. Over the past few
months, doctors and nurses shuttling between hospitals and
patients' homes have provided services to more than 300 patients,
including a 109-year-old man and a two-month-old baby.
</P>
<P>
Medical service contracts have also become popular in the east
China city. Some 250 families in one residential quarter have
signed agreements with medical facilities nearby.
</P>
<P>
"We pay 40 yuan per year, then each member of my family may
have a free medical examination in the year," said a housewife,
adding that doctors will come to her home a few times a year to
give health care advices.
</P>
<P>
The city said that some 200 additional medical stations are
expected to open by the end of this year, offering treatment
as well as information on disease prevention and health care, and
psychological counseling.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
