<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, U.S. Cooperation Improved: Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin said here today that cooperation between Russia with the
United States has been markedly improved in the areas of concern
established at this year's Russia-U.S. summit.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin made the remark while meeting with visiting
U.S. Vice-President Al Gore, who arrived in Moscow on Sunday and
attended the ninth meeting of the Russia-U.S. Economic and
Technological Cooperation Commission on Monday, according to the
President Press Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president praised the commission, saying that
bilateral trade has doubled since the commission was established
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
The joint research program on space is a symbol of the new
relationship between the two countries, Yeltsin added.
</P>
<P>
However, Yeltsin went on to say, the fact that U.S. laws do not
recognize Russia as a market-oriented country, as well as the
harsh conditions set for Russia to join the World Trade
Organization (WTO) have hindered the development of more favorable
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
It is not acceptable that certain Americans intend to announce
some areas of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) as
"U.S. special interests region," and force Russia out of them, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Gore said the U.S. did not want to set up its own spheres of
influence, or try to force Russia away from the region while
developing relations with other members of the CIS.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. is preparing to consolidate the stability and
peace in CIS hot areas with Russia and to pave the way for
mutually beneficial trade in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
