<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0200 GMT September 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- Germany's reinsurance giant Muenchner Rueck Tuesday
announced plans to buy a 20 percent stake in Italy's
second-largest reinsurance company Reale Ri by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Under a letter of intent signed with Reale Ri's parent company
Reale Mutua, which has 90 percent ownership of Reale Ri, Muenchner
Rueck was planning to spend 550 billion lires (about 315 million
U.S. dollars) for the deal. (Germany-Italy-Reinsurers)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his Egyptian
counterpart Hosni Mubarak on Tuesday signed a joint political
declaration and two agreements on cooperation in technology and
crime-control, according to Interfax News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said he was confident the first official visit by the
Egyptian president to Russia since its independence "would make a
breakthrough in all areas of our cooperation."
(Russia-Egypt-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran said Tuesday that it has manufactured its first
jet fighter which features assault ability upon ground targets,
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Iranian army Chief of Staff Ali Shahbazi was quoted as saying
that Iran has made its first jet fighter "Ouj", which will be
tested in a mission in Zulfaqar military exercises near Qom, 150
kilometers south of Iran's capital Tehran.
</P>
<P>
He said the Iranian air force has set up an assembling line of
the jet fighter thanks to the special attention paid by Iran's
Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei. (Iran-Jet Fighter)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The ninth session of the Russian-U.S. joint
commission on economic and technical cooperation
(Chernomyrdin-Gore commission) wound up here Tuesday with more
than 15 inter-governmental and inter-departmental agreements
signed.
</P>
<P>
According to the Itar-Tass news agency, both Russian Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and U.S. Vice President Albert Gore
were satisfied with the results of the
session. (Russia-US-Commission)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German health authorities have put about 100 people
under medical supervision after they were found to have come into
contact with a Ghanaian man suspected of dying of a deadly
disease, Lassa fever, in Germany Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old Ghanaian died Saturday in the western German
city of Mainz after admitting himself to a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
He was suspected of having been infected with the Lassa virus
which regularly hits regions of West Africa and could claim the
lives of up to 40 percent of those infected. The virus is
transmitted through rat urine or human body fluids including
sweat. (Germany-Lassa Fever)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus and Greece agreed on Tuesday that Greek navy
and air force will join their Cypriot counterparts in the planned
military exercises, code-named "Nikiforos '97".
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a meeting between the defense
ministers of Cyprus and Greece in Greek capital Athens today,
according to a press release by the official Press and Information
Office. (Cyprus-Greece-Military Exercises)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The White House, after a senior official stresses
the need for a further stay of peacekeepers in Bosnia beyond next
Summer, said Tuesday that the United States will not change its
policy on Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and other nations must stay in Bosnia for a further
period after the current peacekeeping mission ends in Bosnia next
June to ensure peace takes hold, White House national security
adviser Sandy Berger said earlier Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After Berger's speech at Georgetown University, White House
Michael McCurry said his address wasn't meant to signal change in
U.S. policy on Bosnia. (US-Berger-Bosnia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- The North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) Tuesday
launched a three-week multinational military exercise with
Greece's participation after a long absence.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, code-named "Dynamic Mix '97" and coordinated by
NATO's southern flank headquaters, will include three regional
exercises to be taken place in Greece's Macedonia, Thessaly and
the western Peloponnese.
</P>
<P>
Also participated are Belgium, Britain, Germany, Denmark,
Spain, Portugal, Holland, Norway and the United
States. (Greece-NATO-Exercise) 
</P>
