<HEADLINE> Thick Haze in Indonesia Claims Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Two people have died after
suffering respiratory problems caused by haze, which has been
choking dozens of towns in Sumatra and Kalimantan, Indonesia, an
official said.
</P>
<P>
The two deaths were the first officially recognized fatalities
related to the haze menace, but the official from the Ministry of
People's Welfare declined Tuesday to give details about the
victims, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Suyono, a secretary of the ministry, said more than 32,000
people in Sumatra and Kalimantan have been afflicted with severe
respiratory problems in the last two months by the haze which came
from forest fires there.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that at least 15 forest concession areas
or 400,000 hectares were being razed by fires and 12,000 hectares
were in serious blaze.
</P>
<P>
They estimated that about 20 million people are in danger of
respiratory problems in the country as well as in Malaysia and
Singapore which have also been affected by the haze.
</P>
<P>
Suyono said the government has decided to ask people living
near forest fires to wear a mask to prevent possible diseases.
</P>
<P>
He said people were also requested not to bring children below
ten years old outside their homes while haze was thick.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
