<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Opposition Urged to Support Peace Moves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's four leftist
parties in the ruling People's Alliance government have called on
the main opposition United National Party (UNP) to support the
government's peace proposals, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Lanka Equal Society Party, the Sri Lanka People's Party,
the National Liberation People's Party and the Communist Party
held a joint demonstration in Colombo on Tuesday calling for an
end to the ethnic war and the speedy implementation of the
devolution package.
</P>
<P>
Under the package, more autonomy would be given to Northern and
Eastern provinces, where the Tamil rebels have been fighting a
guerrilla war for a separate state since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The parties urged the UNP to carefully study the proposals and
give their support. The devolution proposals need to win a
two-thirds majority in the 225-seat parliament. The UNP, which
holds 94 parliament seats, hasn't expressed its support yet.
</P>
<P>
The leftists believe that the devolution bill was the only way
to end the ethnic crisis and ensure amity among different
communities.  
</P>
