<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Aid More Poor College Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China will step up efforts to
establish an efficient system for giving financial aid to poor
college students.
</P>
<P>
The central government has allocated 100 million yuan (12
million US dollars) this year to aid poor students in
ministry-managed colleges and universities, Yang Zhoufu, an
official of the State Education Commission (SEC), was quoted by
today's China Daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most local educational departments, colleges and universities
have also taken measures to help poor students, Yang said at a
national conference on aiding poor students being held in central
China's Wuhan city.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released at the meeting, most provinces
and cities have started setting up aid funds including
scholarship, loans, subsidies, work-for-study programs and
tuition-reduction or exemption schemes.
</P>
<P>
The report said that loans will be provided to less well-off
students by the colleges and universities, at an average of 2,000
yuan (240 US dollars) each year.
</P>
<P>
The loans will be awarded on a zero-interest basis with
guarantees. A national loan fund will be established in Beijing to
supervise the administration of the loans.
</P>
<P>
Twenty percent of college students will benefit from the loans,
Yang said.
</P>
<P>
China has 2.8 million college students on campus. Twenty
percent of them are in financial difficulties, and seven percent
of them live in remote and poor areas where annual family incomes
are below 1,000 yuan (120 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The tuition payment system has been thoroughly introduced to
colleges from this autumn's semester, replacing the former
tuition-free system. Students are required to pay 10 to 20 percent
of all education fees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
