<HEADLINE> Panama Begins Cattle Exportation to Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Panama sent its first
shipment of young bulls to Colombia today, initiating a cattle
exportation program to its southern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Virgilio Samaniego, president of the "Azuero" slaughter house,
told reporters that in Panama's central provinces there is a
surplus of young bulls waiting to be exported to Colombia, where
there is a strong demand for beef and breeders are well paid and
earn a good profit.
</P>
<P>
The exports could eventually provide some assistance in helping
the country's economy to recover, Samaniego said.
</P>
<P>
He added that in recent years, Panama's cattle industry has
faced many problems. One of the most serious problems affecting
the country this year is the late drought, which is occurring in
many Panamanian provinces. Farmers and forecasters are blaming the
problem on the weather phenomenon called 'El Nino.'
</P>
<P>
"We asked the government to provide us with 300,000 tons of
cane to feed some 400,000 head of cattle to help ease the crisis,
but we did not receive any support from them," Samaniego said.
</P>
<P>
He added, however, that by using some of the funds from
exportation-related income, the country's agriculture and cattle
sectors have finally managed to ease the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
