<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Food Program Praised for Success of Projects in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese senior official
Tuesday praised the support of the World Food Program (WFP) as
significantly contributing to China's efforts to alleviate
poverty, Today's China Daily said.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the cooperative projects with WFP are successful,"
said Gao Hongbin, director-general of the State Council Leading
Group Office for Poverty Alleviation and Development.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar sponsored by WFP China, Gao emphasized
the role of the WFP in China's campaign to eradicate poverty in
rural areas by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
"By reducing poverty among the population of China, WFP's
programs also contribute to the world," Gao said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the WFP has carried out 59 food-aid programs in
China totalling 768 million US dollars. The recipients cover 184
of China's municipalities and counties, with a total population of
more than 22.3 million.
</P>
<P>
Although, as a result of China's 15 years of work to alleviate
poverty, only 7.1 percent of the rural population are living in
poverty, the existing 58 million people living at or below the
poverty line still pose an arduous task. Almost all these people
are in the central and western parts of the country, living in high
or rocky mountainous areas, deserts, or on the Loess Plateau --
often in ethnic minority regions.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the international poverty level set at a per
capita income of 365 US dollars annually (3,030 yuan), China's
poverty level is 500 yuan (60 US dollars). The per capita income
of China's 800-million rural population reached 1,500 yuan (181 US
dollars) last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Program Launched to Help Poor Farmers in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Since the economic miracle of
the early 1980s enriched millions of farmers, China has turned its
attention to the 58 million needy people in rural areas, reported
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Civil Affairs, China offers
800 million yuan (96 million US dollars) for social relief every
year.
</P>
<P>
The country last year implemented a program to ensure a minimum
cost of living for the impoverished. The program has, up to now,
covered 3.38 million poor farmers in 450 counties throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
No national minimum standard of cost of living has been set,
due to the gap in economic growth between eastern and western
regions. The standard varies from area to area, said Liao Hong, an
official from the Ministry of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The western area, where the destitute is concentrated, needs
more financial aid from both the central and local governments.
</P>
<P>
With limited funds, county governments were quite strict in
identifying needy individuals. Farmers must apply to the village
committees and get approval by the local township governments
before they are granted a card for receiving relief.
</P>
<P>
People who become deficient because of gambling, extravagance
in building houses or wedding and funeral ceremonies are not
allowed to benefit from the program.
</P>
<P>
Local governments also exempted the agriculture tax and offered
free health care and education to cash-trapped people.
</P>
<P>
Farmers who have children in the army and are unable to take
care of themselves also enjoy the preferential policy.
</P>
<P>
As part of the program, China offers two billion yuan (240
million US dollars) for disaster relief every year.
</P>
<P>
People who suffer from a sudden natural disaster can hope to
receive help to meet their basic needs.
</P>
<P>
An old-age pension, as part of an overall rural social security
system sponsored by the government, will be set up to help aged
people, who most likely become poor when they cannot till the
land.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Civil Affairs, one-fifth of people
aged between 20 and 60 in rural areas have now bought an old-age
pension. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
