<HEADLINE> Changyu Wine Listing A Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China's biggest wine maker
was listed in Shenzhen Tuesday on the B-share market, designed to
attract overseas investors, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Despite weak market interest, shares in the Changyu Pioneer
Wine Co. made a satisfactory debut, rising 0.45 to 3.70 HK dollars
from their issue price of 3.25 HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
Fear of the accelerated expansion of Chinese stock markets
announced at the 15th National Congress of the Chinese Communist
Party caused share prices in Shenzhen to fall sharply, losing 13
percent in the first two trading days of the week.
</P>
<P>
Even in such an unfavorable market environment, Changyu shares
reached a high of 3.90 HK dollars after opening at 3.60 HK
dollars, and were the most actively traded with 12.05 million
shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
In anticipation of a bright future for China's wine industry,
the company's 88 million B-shares had attracted active interest
from overseas investors when they were issued at the beginning of
September.
</P>
<P>
Proceeds from the issue, amounting to 280 million yuan (33.7
million US dollars), would be used to fund the company's expansion
program to raise wine production to 73,000 tons by 1999 from the
current level of 40,000 tons, said company president Sun Liqiang.
</P>
<P>
The company plans to raise further funds for expansion by
listing on the A-share market -- which is for domestic investors
-- next year, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
