<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "El Nino" Effects May Last Until 1998: Peruvian Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The weather effects as a result
of the "El Nino" climatic phenomenon may last until June 1998,
Peruvian experts have predicted.
</P>
<P>
The extension of such effects are accumulating a huge mass of
warm water in the sea, Pablo Lagos, Director of the Peru Institute
of Geophysics (PIG) was quoted as saying by the local press today.
</P>
<P>
The scientist said this abnormality is caused by sudden
west-to-east changes in the direction of trade winds in the
western Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Such a fact could be increasing a phenomenon called
"Thermoclimate," or hot water strips, which are getting
progressively deeper and raising the temperature not to a normal
of 4 or 5 degrees Celsius, but 6 or even 7 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
Lagos said heavy rains are expected in north of Peru, from next
November on and also in the "Sierra Central" zone. He urged
competent authorities to take necessary actions to to counter
possible problems.
</P>
<P>
For his part, PIG president Ronald Woodman said the 1998 "El
Nino" phenomenon would be as intense as the one which occurred in
the 1982-1983 period.
</P>
<P>
He said that as a result of such a phenomenon, overwhelming
rains are expected over the northern coast of Peru. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
