<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica to Combat Deadly Hanta Virus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rican government
is planning a series of preventive measures to combat the Hanta
Virus, which is the cause of a highly contagious disease that has
resulted in death in nearly 50 percent of the cases reported, the
Health Ministry reported today.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Health Fernando Marin said the ministry will
provide special training for physicians that will enable them to
detect the virus and infected individuals.
</P>
<P>
He called on all Costa Ricans to improve their health habits
and to try and improve their living conditions, such as washing
their hands before meals, making sure that food is cooked properly
and thoroughly before eating, and to make sure that food is
properly stored.
</P>
<P>
This year the government says it will provide medical equipment
capable of detecting the presence of the virus in individuals if
and when they enter Costa Rican territory, said Marin.
</P>
<P>
According to the Pan American Health Organization, the virus is
transmitted by rodents, primarily from their droppings, and also
rotten food.
</P>
<P>
The disease causes fever, breathing difficulties, headache and
stomach ache, internal hemorrhaging and vomiting.
</P>
<P>
It is possible that the Hanta Virus could spread over all Latin
American countries if it is not controlled.
</P>
<P>
An outbreak of the virus took place in a Chilean rural area
called Arica, which borders Peru and Bolivia; one person
reportedly died from the infection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Coal Miners, Now Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Some 1,500 laid-off coal
miners in Central China's Hunan province are now busy farming on
local barren hillsides.
</P>
<P>
Since most of Hunan's coal mines are located in remote hilly
land, the province has encouraged laid-off workers there to switch
to agriculture to earn a living.
</P>
<P>
The Luota Coal Mine, located in the western part of the
province, called on its staff to grow Chinese chestnuts, ginger
and tobacco on 85 hectares of land on barren hillsides.
</P>
<P>
They also raised more than 800 goats.
</P>
<P>
"We are working hard for a good harvest," said one
miner-turned farmer.
</P>
<P>
Some coal mining companies have also joined hands with villages
nearby for agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
The Zixing Coal Mining Administration signed a contract with a
local feed-processing company to co-produce fodder. They rented a
piece of land from the city government to grow sweet potatoes,
which has given 900-plus laid-off workers new jobs.
</P>
<P>
The administration also rented a reservoir for its 100 laid-off
workers to raise 200,000 fish and 6,000 ducks, and the output
value is expected to hit 2.6 million yuan this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
