<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OCA Decides Thailand Continue to Host 1998 Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Executive Board of
the Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) today decided to continue give
the chance of hosting the 1998 Asian games to Bangkok, Thailand,
although concerns over the preparations for the games still
remain.
</P>
<P>
President of OCA, a Kuwaiti Prince, Ahmad Fahd Al-Sabah told a
press conference after a four hour meeting of the Executive Board
that this is the final decision concerning the hosting right of
Bangkok which was made 14 months ahead of the games to be held in
December 1998.
</P>
<P>
He said the members of the board examined and discussed the
situation in Bangkok and the progress of the preparations for the
game and a Memorandum of Agreement was reached.
</P>
<P>
He added that a meeting of the OCA would be held on December 15
to be followed by meetings of all sub-committees to carry out
examinations of various aspects of the games preparations.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok won the right to hold the games seven years ago. But
OCA officials said there had been very little progress in
preparing for the event and that there was major disorganization
in the organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
The OCA called the emergency meeting last month last month
amid growing doubts over the success of the games following a
spate of resignations of the Bangkok Asian Games Organizing
Committee (BAGOC), unsigned sponsorship contracts and accusations
of political meddling in the games organization.
</P>
<P>
A 43-member delegation arrived in Kuwait well before the
meeting was held this afternoon to convince the board members on
Thailand's ability and readiness to host the 1998 Asian games.
</P>
<P>
The BAGOC has given new assurance to the OCA that the
preparations in all respects would be completed three months
ahead of the games schedule.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah said that "as OCA, we will keep following the
preparations of the Bangkok Asian Games Organizing Committee if
they are ready to solve all the problems" surrounding the
preparations.
</P>
<P>
He also said "I feel more comfortable and more trust in
Bangkok to continue the preparations for the games."
</P>
<P>
Bangkok hosted three previous Asian games in the past with the
first being in 1966, the second in 1970 and the third in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah hopes the Bangkok Asian games would reach the level of
last Hiroshima games which he thought was one of best games held
in Asian history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
