<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child Gun Toll Down in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The number of children and
teen-agers killed by guns dropped in 1995 for the first time in
more than a decade, according to government statistics released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The information was released by the Children Defense Fund and
confirmed by the National Center for Health Statistics. The
statistics were available in July but had not been broken down to
focus on Americans aged 19 and under.
</P>
<P>
Overall, 5,285 people aged 19 and under were killed by guns in
1995, a 9.4 percent drop from 1994.
</P>
<P>
But there are still 14 children and teen-agers killed by guns
each day, on average.
</P>
<P>
"It's hard to take too much joy in that, but 14 is better than
16," said Kim Wade, assistant general counsel of the fund.
</P>
<P>
The number and rate of gun deaths have been climbing since
1983, when just under 3,000 children and teens were killed by
guns.
</P>
<P>
Six in 10 of the deaths are homicides, which have fallen two
years in a row. But the drop in 1995 was dramatic -- 9.2 percent
-- driving the overall death rate down to seven deaths out of
every 100,000 Americans under 19, said Lois Fingerhut, an analyst
with the government's statistics office.
</P>
<P>
The homicide rate has been dropping for adults, as well.
</P>
<P>
Suicides dropped 7.3 percent to 1,450 in 1995, and
unintentional deaths dropped 14.1 percent, to 440.
</P>
<P>
Also Tuesday, children's hospitals announced a campaign to
highlight accidental deaths that occur when a child finds a
parent's gun. Public service advertisements are set to appear in
30 national magazines, and children's hospitals in more than 100
cities will ask local television stations to run them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
