<HEADLINE> Canadian Government Lay Out Plans for the Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government said
today that it's time to start reinvesting in the future now that
it has almost won the battle against the deficit.
</P>
<P>
In a throne speech to open the 36th parliament, the government
laid out its plans for the next few years.
</P>
<P>
"Stimulating job creation and economic growth has been,
remains, and will continue to be a major objective of the
government of Canada," said the speech, which was read in the
Senate by Governor General Romeo LeBlanc on behalf of Jean
Chretien's government.
</P>
<P>
The government will continue its present course and take
further action to encourage new investment, to create new jobs,
and to generate the national wealth.
</P>
<P>
It also predicted that the budget will be balanced "no later
than fiscal year 1998-99", that is, no later than March 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"The government has regained the ability to address priorities
of Canadians while living within its means," the speech declared.
</P>
<P>
"It is now in the position to take strategic investments in our
children and our youth, our health, our communities, and our
knowledge and creativity while continuing to improve the nation's
finances," it said.
</P>
<P>
The government promised today to eventually double the 850
million dollars (610 million USD) in federal tax credits for poor
families.
</P>
<P>
And a "children's agenda" promised in the June election will be
put together in collaboration with the provinces.
</P>
<P>
On the medicare front, the government will bring in legislation
cementing a promise to stabilize health funding for the provinces.
</P>
<P>
It will also work with the provinces on promises to expand
medicare by setting up pharmacare and home care pilot projects.
</P>
<P>
The government also promised an effort to boost high-tech
industries like aerospace, pharmaceuticals and telecommunications
and to help small businesses.
</P>
<P>
On the touchy issue of national unity, the government said it
will "take a very broad and encompassing approach to promoting and
strengthening our unity."
</P>
<P>
"The government will bring frankness and clarity to any debate
that puts into question the future existence or unity of Canada,"
and will ensure Quebecers have a better idea of "the true
complexity and difficulty" with respect to separation.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts here say that the throne speech emphasized the
"stay the course" approach adopted by the ruling Liberals in the
Spring campaign, and contained few new ideas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
