<HEADLINE> Brazil Holds "One China" Policy, Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Brazil would continue
to adopt the "One China" policy in its foreign affairs, in the
United Nations and in all other international organizations, Luis
Felipe Lampreia, Minister of External Relations of Brazil, said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Lampreia made the remarks during his meeting with Chinese
Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen, both being here to
attend the 52nd Session of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that China and Brazil have enjoyed smooth development
of bilateral relations, and the two countries have kept in close
consultation in the international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Qian said china and Brazil have a broad aspect for the
cooperation in the area of high-tech, and the two countries have
joined the development of a satellite for exploring earth
resources.
</P>
<P>
Qian also briefed Lampreia on the 15th National Congress of the
Chinese Communist Party, which closed in Beijing recently.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Lampreia expressed satisfaction over the latest
development of the relations between the two countries, saying
Brazil Government hope to further deepen and extend the good
relations the two countries are enjoying now.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Brazil would continue to adopt the "One China"
policy in its foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
On China's joining to the World Trade Organization (WTO), Qian
said China has been making serious efforts to join WTO, and China
had made significant progress in its recent talks with some
countries.
</P>
<P>
Qian hoped that China's talks with Brazil will also get
fruitful results.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also exchanged views on the reform
of the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
