<HEADLINE> Chinese, British Foreign Ministers Talk over Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen discussed bilateral and international
issues with British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook during their
meeting here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Qian confirmed the current relations between China and Britain.
He said that both sides had very good meetings and talks during
the transition of Hong Kong's sovereignty earlier this year. Both
sides expressed the willingness to further the bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that now the two countries are preparing for the
exchange of visits at high levels. Britain's economic and trade
links with China proved to be among the first few big gainers in
such exchanges between China and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that the China visit by British Prime Minister Toni
Blair will be an important event in the bilateral relations. He
also extended his invitation to Cook and other British officials
to visit China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Foreign Minister also said that Britain will become
the rotating chairman of the European Union next year and will
host the Second Asian-European Summit. "We hope that Britain would
play a constructive role in developing the relations between Asia
and Europe. He said he hoped that both sides would continue to
deepen their mutual understanding through exchanges and
cooperation and on the basis of equality and mutual respect, with
the aim of promoting dialogues and eliminating confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Cook agreed with Qian's comments on the bilateral relations,
adding that the smooth hand-over of Hong Kong was made possible by
the cooperative efforts. He said that the bilateral economic and
trade relations are showing a good development trend and
potentials for further expansion.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Blair and other ministerial officials and he
himself are all looking forward to the China visit at an early
date. He agreed on Qian's view that countries should replace
confrontation with cooperation and dialogues in international
affairs.
</P>
<P>
On the reform of the United Nations, the Chinese foreign
minister said that reform should U.N. reform should reflect the
will of developing countries and the needs of different regions.
Reform should lead to higher efficiency, better serve member
states, and serve the two goals of peace and development.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also discussed the cooperation in
finance and navigation and other international issues of common
concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
