<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Says no Change in U.S. Bosnia Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The White House, after a
senior official stresses the need for a further stay of
peacekeepers in Bosnia beyond next Summer, today said that the
United States will not change its policy on Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and other nations must stay in Bosnia for a further
period after the current peacekeeping mission ends in Bosnia next
June to ensure peace takes hold, White House national security
adviser Sandy Berger said earlier today.
</P>
<P>
After Berger's speech at Georgetown University, White House
Michael McCurry said his address wasn't meant to signal change in
U.S. policy on Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"He has not shifted the ground on the president's determination
to meet the timetable" for withdrawing current troops, said
McCurry, who explained the speech was aimed at the "cut-and-run
crowd."
</P>
<P>
"It's a direct response to those that have said somehow or
other we can walk away from this international tragedy and leave
it to others to continue to do the work of rebuilding civil
society in Bosnia-Herzegovina in the aftermath of the worst ethnic
and military conflict in Europe since World War II," McCurry told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
In the major speech at the Georgetown University, Berger
cautioned that an early pullout could risk war in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Stabilization Force (SFOR) in Bosnia, led by the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), will end its mission in June
1998 as scheduled, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
But Berger emphasized what President Bill Clinton and Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright have indicated for months that "the
international community's engagement will continue" beyond the
deadline.
</P>
<P>
However, he failed to point out how long the multinational
forces should stay in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Berger acknowledged that "progress is painfully slow on many
fronts."
</P>
<P>
"Less than two years after Dayton (Agreement was signed) and
after so much devastation, the job is far from done," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Bosnia still stands on a tightrope, inching towards a better
future but still not past the point of danger," Berger added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the prominent indicted war criminals "remain at
large," large majority of refugees remain unable to return home,
the Bosnian Serbs are "in the grip of an intense struggle and the
media isn't independent; and economic reconstruction is spotty.
</P>
<P>
"We should not give up on justice and reward aggression,"
Berger said. "Partition also would be wrong because it would send
the message to ethnic fanatics everywhere that the international
community will allow redrawing of borders by force."
</P>
<P>
Ending the commitment in the region could undermine NATO and
lead to more bloodshed in Bosnia and beyond, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
"If (the) Dayton (peace agreement) fails, Bosnia will almost
certainly slide back into conflict, potentially leading to a wider
war in Southeastern Europe," Berger said.
</P>
<P>
"It would undermine NATO's credibility at a critical moment
when the alliance is preparing for new members and new missions,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
