<HEADLINE> Qian, Thapa Satisfied with Sino-Nepalese Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and Nepalese Foreign Minister
Kamal Thapa today expressed their satisfaction over growing
friendly relations between the two neighboring countries and
stressed the importance for continued mutual support in broad
fields.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to Nepal
last year was of great importance to the consolidation of
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Nepalese friendship has a long history and there is no
any problem between the two neighbors, Qian said, but both sides
have been enjoying fruitful cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed the thanks to Nepal for its support to China on
the issues of Taiwan, Tibet and human rights.
</P>
<P>
He noted that it is necessary for the developing nations to
extend mutual sympathy and support in their common efforts to
safeguard stability and development.
</P>
<P>
Thapa extended to Qian his congratulations to the successful
convention of the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China which concluded last week.
</P>
<P>
Thapa said, Nepal is China's friendly neighbor and the Nepalese
people closely follows China's development and appreciate China's
progress.
</P>
<P>
The Nepalese foreign minister reiterated that the Nepalese
government will adhere to a "one China" policy, and will never let
any one to use the Nepalese soil to carry out activities aiming to
split China.
</P>
<P>
Nepal also will continue to stand by China on the human rights
issue, he stated.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers hold that the two countries will have
greater opportunities in expanding their economic cooperation with
the economic growth in their nations.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the two governments should encourage and support
their enterprises to actively join such cooperations, they
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
