<HEADLINE> Canadian FM to Attend UN General Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Affairs
Minister Lloyd Axworthy said today he will attend the 52nd session
of the United Nations General Assembly in New York, which convenes
late this month.
</P>
<P>
"Canada has always supported the UN and has taken a leading
role in its activities over the past 51 years," Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that his country is seeking a seat on the UN
Security Council for 1999/2000.
</P>
<P>
"Our resulting capacity to influence the direction and policies
of the UN, particularly on peacekeeping, peacebuilding and other
human security issues, would be greatly enhanced," he said.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy will also take advantage of the chance to advance
international support for the newly negotiated treaty banning
anti-personnel landmines, adopted in Oslo, Norway, last week.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the minister is expected to have some bilateral
and multilateral meetings while he is in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
