<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Researcher Warns against Aid Vaccine Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A German researcher today warned
a Chicago doctors' group not to realize its plan to conduct AIDS
vaccine test on human bodies, saying that the experiment is
nothing more than a "suicide".
</P>
<P>
Under a plan of the Chicago-based group, 50 volunteers, 39 of
them are doctors themselves, would be injected with a live but
weakened strain of the AIDS virus HIV to prove that the strain
could serve as a vaccine that would train the human body's immune
system to resist full-strength HIV.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German MDR radio today, Dr. Reinhard
Kurth, who head Germany's Robert Koch Institute, criticized the
volunteers as "a suicide squad" who are needlessly going to put
their lives at risk.
</P>
<P>
Kurth admitted that the vaccine test did have achieved some
effect on monkeys, but he also pointed to the fact that some young
monkeys had also developed AIDS during the tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-Japan Military Ties to Be Enhanced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 23 (Xinhua) -- With the new defense
cooperation guidelines going into effect, military relationship
between the United States and Japan will be enhanced, officials of
both countries reaffirmed.
</P>
<P>
The 16-page guidelines, revised on the basis of the 1978
version, was made public here today.
</P>
<P>
"It is really based upon mutual collaboration trying to device
the mechanisms whereby we can have greater coordination of
activities," said U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen at a joint
press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The press conference followed a U.S.-Japan Security
Consultative Committee (SCC) meeting which adopted the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Representing the U.S. at the meeting was also Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright while Japan was represented by Cohen's
counterpart Fumio Kyuma and Albright's counterpart Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines will "reinforce our security alliance which is
crucial to our common security and foundation of all our bilateral
ties," Albright told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Our partnership with Japan is central to many of the issues
we'll be working on this week in New York, from nuclear
non-proliferation and United Nations reform to protecting
environment and promoting development in Africa," she said.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. policy in Asia Pacific has several pillars: cooperation
with Japan, engagement with China, eventual peace on the Korean
Peninsula and the presence of 100000 U.S. troops in the region,"
Cohen said at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi said that "with the new guidelines, I trust Japan-U.S.
defense cooperation can proceed in a closer manner."
</P>
<P>
Kyuma also emphasized that the guidelines clarify cooperation
in the areas and roles that the two countries will play in the
post-war era.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have ensured that the new guidelines "are not
aimed at any third country".
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing country-specific or geographically specific"
in the guidelines, Albright said, declaring that "it does not
change our one-China policy".
</P>
<P>
According to a joint statement issued at the end of the SCC
meeting, both the U.S. and Japan "shared the view that it is
extremely important for the stability and prosperity of the
region that China play a positive and constructive role, and in
this context, stressed the continued interest of both countries in
furthering cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and Japanese officials expressed their intention to
"explain" the guidelines to China, South Korea and other countries
in the region to alleviate their concerns about the impact of
enhancement of U.S.-Japan military ties when approaching the 21st
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970924.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
