<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Supports U.N. Reform Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Japan today pledged to
take actions to support the reform of the United Nations and
voiced backing to the reform package put forward by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during the general debates of the 52nd session of the
U.N. General Assembly, Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi said
that the purpose of reforming the world body is to strengthen its
functions to further enable it to fully accomplish its tasks.
</P>
<P>
"We earnestly hope that the reform of the United Nations as a
whole will gather momentum" through Annan's proposals, Obuchi
said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if the U.N. was unable to reform itself to meet
the demands of the coming age, but simply engages in an aimless
repetition of detailed arguments in which each member states
pursue its own interests, the confidence of the international
community in the organization would be severely undermined.
</P>
<P>
"We must be aware that at this moment we were standing at a
crucial crossroads. It is the very moment at which we must summon
the political will to decide on the outlines of U.N. reform," he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi's speech indicated that Japan has joined a majority of
member states in expressing support to the reform efforts by Annan
who became the head of the U.N. administration on January 1 this
year.
</P>
<P>
He said that Japan believes reforms relating to the Security
Council, finance and development are the "three pillars" of the
U.N. reforms.
</P>
<P>
Referring to current financial crisis of the largest
international organization, Obuchi said that Japan wanted to
emphasize again that it is the obligation of member states to pay
their assessed contributions in full, and that member states in
arrears should make every effort to eliminate them.
</P>
<P>
Dues owed by member states to the United Nations have totaled
2.3 billion U.S. dollars. The United States alone reportedly owes
nearly 1.5 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
